presentation of materials do not imply any expression of opinion whatsoever on the United Nations concerning access to energy and poverty reduction. Copyright \u00a9 2006 UNDP United Nations Development Programme Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok UN Service Building Rajdamnern Nok Avenue Bangkok 10200 Thailand http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th/practices/energy_env/rep-por ISBN 10: 92-1-126200-3 ISBN 13: 978-92-1-126200-1 Preface Six years have passed since the signing of the historic Millennium Declaration. As nations are strengthening their efforts to reach the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs), energy as a critical input for development has yet to be adequately and appropriately addressed. It is a well-established fact that access to reliable and affordable energy services helps improve efficiency and productivity, enhances living standards and overall livelihoods through quantitative and qualitative impacts on health, literacy and education. Therefore, priority measures need to be enacted for its affordable access to all nations, and communities within the nations. Recognizing the critical need to support countries in extending the access of modern energy services in a cost-effective manner to the poor, the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), through its Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) in Asia- Pacific, commissioned national-level rapid gap assessments in 15 countries in Asia and 15 countries in the Pacific. The primary aims of these assessments were to identify gaps in drivers that link energy access to poverty reduction, and to identify priority needs to enhance access to affordable modern energy services. The framework for the assessments was developed through two sub-regional consultation meetings held in Bangkok, Thailand (August 2005) and Apia, Samoa (September 2005). In finalizing the framework for the country-level assessments, gender concerns and its linkages to energy poverty were identified as crucial factors that needed special attention. As a result, two sub-regional assessments on energy and gender \u2013 one for the Asian region and the other for the Pacific region \u2013 were commissioned. However, as the messages in the two assessments complemented one another, they were combined into this single Asia-Pacific regional report, Will Tomorrow be Brighter than Today? Addressing gender concerns in energy for poverty reduction in the Asia-Pacific region. This Report critically iii Countries in the Asia-Pacific region need to pay adequate attention to energy services if they are to meet the MDGs analyses the gender-related issues affecting the promotion of energy access and proposes pragmatic recommendations on mainstreaming gender concerns in strengthening energy access. Specifically, the Report attempts to establish links between energy access, gender equity and poverty reduction; identifies critical gaps in access to energy services; and recommends options for mainstreaming gender into energy access policy strategies and programming. It is hoped that this work will be of relevance to national policy makers, development partners, energy service providers, civil society organiza- tions and other interested persons, including academia, to preparing and implementing gender-sensitive energy services policies and projects to promote access to modern energy services for the poor and the unserved. iv This report is an outcome of the partnership initiatives of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Asia-Pacific Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR). It benefits from a year and a half of collaboration between the UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok (RCB), UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo (RCC), UNDP Country Offices in the Asia-Pacific region and key national, as well as regional, experts.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metada