Deportations to the Pacific Islands from the Unites States, Australia and New Zealand was written and developed in conjunction with Siobhan Sparkes McNamara, United Nations Volunteer with important support and guidance from the Government of the United States \u2013 Department of Homeland Security, Government of Australia \u2013 Department of Immigration and Citizenship and the Government of New Zealand \u2013 Department of Labour Immigration Services. Special thanks are due to the Commonwealth Youth Programme \u2013 Programme Manager Paul Seilala Peteru, Dr Susan Vize United Nations Educational, Scientific, Cultural Organization (UNESCO) and Jennifer Nicita. Natalia Pereira (n.pereira@counsellor.com) was a consultant for the Crisis Prevention and Recovery Unit at UNDP Pacific Centre. She holds a Master of International Development, post-graduate degree in Social Work and a Bachelor degree in Social Science. She has been a youth development practitioner for over a decade and her specialization includes: human migration, resettlement and reintegration. Siobhan Sparkes McNamara (siobhan4285@googlemail.com) was a United Nations Volunteer for the Crisis Prevention and Recovery Unit at UNDP Pacific Centre. She holds a Master of Laws in Human Rights, Justice and Conflict and a Bachelor of Arts in Law. Her areas of work include humanitarian assistance, displaced persons and family reunification. Contents Acronyms vii Foreword viii Guide Structure ix Introduction 1 Pacific Approaches and Partnerships 3 Part One: Legislation Governing Criminal Deportations to the Pacific Islands from the United States, Australia and New Zealand 5 Objective 6 Structure 6 1. What is the Legislation that governs deportation in the United States of America, Australia and New Zealand? 7 2. Which classes of non-citizens are potentially deportable? 8 3. What types of criminal activity make a non-citizen deportable? 9 4. What are the removal procedures for each of the countries? 13 5. What bilateral agreements and/ or diplomatic Memorandums of Understanding (MoUs) with recipient States must be in place in order to deport? 17 6. What are the relevant human rights standards in the context of deportation? 18 Overview & Comparisons 23 Bibliography 25 Part Two: Working with Deportees in an Ethical Manner: Approaches for Engagement and Service Provision 27 Scope 28 Ethical Approaches for Engagement and Service Provision 29 Appendix 1 \u2013 Aggravated Felonies 36 Appendix 2: International human rights norms applicable to the United States of America, Australia and New Zealand 37 Appendix 3: Capacity Assessment Tool for Service Providers 41 References 50 Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues vii vi List of Tables Table 1: Category of crimes that constitutes moral turpitude 10 Table 2: International Human Rights Norms 37 List of IN FOCUS Boxes IN FOCUS 1: What do we mean by ethics?", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a5f3ac6c-72fb-4e6a-8178-b95be8adca35": {"__data__": {"id_": "a5f3ac6c-72fb-4e6a-8178-b95be8adca35", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/working-deported-individuals-pacific-legal-and-ethical-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/working-deported-individuals-pacific-legal-and-ethical-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Pr