. (2) The expulsion of such a refugee shall be only in pursuance of a decision reached in accordance with due process of law. Except where compelling reasons of national security otherwise require, the refugee shall be allowed to submit evidence to clear himself, and to appeal to and be represented for the purpose before competent authority or a person or persons specially designated by the competent authority. USA: 1968 (only ratified 1967 Protocol) Australia: 1954 New Zealand: 1960 Article 33(1) Prohibition of expulsion or return (\u201crefoulement\u201d) (1) No Contracting State shall expel or return (\u201crefouler\u201d) a refugee in any manner whatsoever to the frontiers of territories where his life or freedom would be threatened on account of his race, religion, nationality, membership of a particular social group or political opinion. Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues 42 41 Appendix 3: Capacity Assessment Tool for Service Providers The capacity assessment tool is mainly intended for staff/volunteers in civil society organizations (CSOs), although it may also be useful for government departments aiming to provide services to deported individuals. It has been designed to be self-administered by a service provider or as a tool to facilitate group discussions about adequate service provision in a workshop setting. The outcome of the capacity assessment tool will highlight capacity strengths as well as identify needs and gaps. These needs and gaps will be entered into the capacity development action- plan that will serve", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8aa3b3f2-6c35-492a-98b9-4093f46e9e5d": {"__data__": {"id_": "8aa3b3f2-6c35-492a-98b9-4093f46e9e5d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/working-deported-individuals-pacific-legal-and-ethical-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/working-deported-individuals-pacific-legal-and-ethical-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3f5808fe4ec6c05b4c6313acad63fb66762aa379ee693844c81e6f30ae33beeb"}}, "hash": "3f5808fe4ec6c05b4c6313acad63fb66762aa379ee693844c81e6f30ae33beeb", "text": "as a basic action-oriented and time framed tool to assist organizations in delegating responsibilities and resources to achieve maximum capacity.78 Key Concept: Capacity Development UNDP defines capacity development as the process through which individuals, organizationsand societies obtain, strengthen and maintain the capabilities to set and achieve their own development objectives over time.79 Specific Capacity Areas The following three capacity areas have been identified as critical to an organizations ability to respond to the needs of their service users, in this case deported individuals, as well as its own ability to efficiently manage its own governance and programmatic areas. \u2022 Organisational Capacity This capacity area looks at the presence of structures, systems and strategies within the organization that would allow it to effectively function and perform at its most efficient capability. It is by no means an exhaustive list; however it offers service providers with a basic list to begin discussions (see Recommended Resources). \u2022 Advocacy and Communication Capacity This capacity area looks at the organizations ability to effectively create, sustain and promote networking and partnerships with other organizations, government and/or donor agencies so as to respond relevantly to beneficiaries and the current operating environment. \u2022 Programming and Technical Capacity This capacity area looks at various forms of programming and technical capacities that organizations may and may not provide. Generally, when responding to the needs of deported individuals it would be advised that an exhaustive social service needs assessments is conducted to determine appropriate programming and adequate technical capacities required. This may be done in various forms (see Recommended Resources) however, this tool provides an initial basic and easy model. Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues 44 43 Capacity Assessment Tool Organizational Capacity Specific Capacity Area Clear need for increased capacity Basic level of capacity Moderate level of capacity High level of capacity Comments The organization is registered with all legal requirements up to standard Vision, mission & values clearly stated & shared in the organization Organization has a board of management represented by women & men from diverse socio- political backgrounds Organization has a clearly set out organizational structure, which includes a legal constitution, roles & responsibilities etc. Project management are consistent with all stages of the project cycle Projects are consulted with all relevant stakeholders particularly beneficiaries Projects are implemented with clear & logical work plans & budgets Clear recruitment policies & procedures Policy & procedure manuals that have documented staff remunerations, job descriptions, grievances procedures etc. System for reviewing and managing staff/volunteer performance, training & development Financial management systems are implemented that prevent fraud & record financial transactions Clear procedures for managing projects/organizational budget are implemented & understood by staff Yearly audit is conduct & recommendations implemented Gender is mainstreamed into organizations strategic plan & programming Resource mobilization strategy implemented & is executed by management board & staff Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues 46 45 Advocacy, Policy & Communication Capacity Specific Capacity Area Clear need for increased capacity Basic level of capacity Moderate level of capacity High level of capacity Comments Advocacy strategy has clear & logical objectives that are consistent with set activities & materials Advocacy activities & materials are based on research & adequate for intended audiences Advocacy activities & materials are consulted with key stakeholders Policy is guided by national policy frameworks and/or international best practise Policy development & review is guided by key stakeholders particularly beneficiaries of services Organization engages policy makers, international organizations and/or funding bodies in policy discussions Organization participates in policy advocacy, lobbying & dissemination Communication strategy has clear & logical objectives that are consistent with set activities & materials Communication activities & materials are adequate for intended audiences Communication activities & materials are consulted with key stakeholders Organization has a networking & collaboration strategy Organization maintains collaborative relationships with government, private sector, media & other CSOs Programming & Technical Capacity Specific Capacity Area Clear need for increased capacity Basic level of capacity Moderate level High level of capacity Comments Participation of beneficiaries Programme staff/volunteer use participatory approaches to programme development Programme staff/volunteers have educational/skill development opportunities Participatory approaches to programme development are reflected in the organization strategy & planning Health & Wellbeing Support Staff/volunteers through educational/skills development have basic health care skills Staff/volunteers have access to a clear health care referral list/ record Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9c2b2afd-36d8-4acf-a73b-49930132ece5": {"__data__": {"id_": "9c2b2afd-36d8-4acf-a73b-49930132ece5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/working-deported-individuals-pacific-legal-and-ethical-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Working with Deported Individuals in the Pacific: Legal and Ethical Issues", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/working-deported-individuals-pacific-legal-and-ethical-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b5e7b3a91b6d2d4e45c5aa6f16eff13640027f7121b19e4e21e02dfe2c6b7dd5"}, "3": {"node_id": "e5ba5061-4614-4376-b93e-6eed6e87cbe6", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/working-deported-individuals-pacific-legal-and-ethical-issues", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "53ff53acca09fc7aebfb8854f429ac28660ae05a225b1e39f402bbdfa050758c"}},