re taken from Flickr.com\u00ae; photographers are gratefully acknowledged. - 3 - ABBREVIATIONS AND ACRONYMS AB Appellate Body ACP Africa, Caribbean and Paci\ufb01c AMS Aggregate Measurement of Support AOA Agreement on Agriculture APTII Asia-Paci\ufb01c Trade and Investment Initiative ASEAN Association of Southeast Asian Nations ATC Agreement on Textiles and Clothing BTA Bilateral Trade Agreement DDA Doha Development Agenda DSB Dispute Settlement Body DSU Dispute Settlement Understanding EEC European Economic Community EFTA European Free Trade Area EU European Union FTA Free Trade Agreement G-6 Group of Six G-20 Group of Twenty GATS General Agreement on Trade in Services GATT General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade GNP Gross National Product IF Integrated Framework for Trade-Related Technical Assistance IPR Intellectual Property Rights LDC Least Developed Countries MDGs Millennium Development Goals MFN Most Favoured Nation MTN Multilateral Trading Negotiations NAFTA North America Free Trade Agreement NAMA Non-Agricultural Market Access ROO Rules of Origin RTA Regional Trade Agreement SAFTA South Asia Free Trade Area SDT Special and Differential Treatment SPS Sanitary and Phyto-Sanitary measures SSG Special Safeguard SSM Special Safeguard Mechanism T&C Textiles and Clothing TDS Trade-Distorting Subsidy TPA Trade Promotion Authority TRIPS Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights UNDP United Nations Development Programme UPOV International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants US United States WIPO World Intellectual Property Organization WTO World Trade Organization - 4 - FOREWORD The World Trade Organization (WTO) is a multilateral framework for the conduct of international trade in goods and services and also for the protection of intellectual property rights. Agreements in the WTO cover areas of trade in goods (which includes subsidies, dumping, technical barriers to trade, tariff reduction, etc.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a72a7c2f-e254-40d0-834b-ee1716fa8fb5": {"__data__": {"id_": "a72a7c2f-e254-40d0-834b-ee1716fa8fb5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b345b86d43dabcdcde7ea2712caeb301235475adacd2e9fea6f464890e1f4a50"}, "2": {"node_id": "02b31595-ef95-4c1f-96a2-3a68ab352fff", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "dfc44cb9e8e8658d26427a44a831a3c9a41f3c2f130a63f93b09941013ab540a"}}, "hash": "081829af8caa466729e683a293f08813bcb4e9c8e4db271403e15bd6d70bc953", "text": "), trade in services, protection of intellectual property rights, and the process of settling disputes for enforcement of rights and obligations. The current negotiation emerging from the Doha Ministerial Declaration of 2001 is expected to address economic and human development concerns, with an agenda of negotiation covering a wide range of subjects. The suspension of the current WTO negotiations on 24 July 2006 can be attributed to some of the structural and operational problems of the WTO and the complexities of the issues as well as the diversities in the interests of the countries. The Handbook explains, in simple language and layout, the general principles and processes of the WTO. It was initially prepared by UNDP for training of South Asian economic journalists in December 2005. The author elaborates on the signi\ufb01cant decisions that have been made in previous negotiations in relation to issues covered in the current negotiations launched by the Doha Ministerial Declaration in 2001. As the suspension of the negotiations shows, the asymmetrical negotiating power of developed countries prevails. Apart from pursuing their aims in the WTO negotiations, they are also likely to intensify their efforts in bilateral and regional free trade", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "94878294-09ef-4ba0-aede-a2af29524813": {"__data__": {"id_": "94878294-09ef-4ba0-aede-a2af29524813", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f02b9c43f0edbaf97f8171b45f3c8e33322ed8b74611711672b135d122bdff57"}}, "hash": "f02b9c43f0edbaf97f8171b45f3c8e33322ed8b74611711672b135d122bdff57", "text": "agreements (BTAs/ RTAs), such as on intellectual property rights, services, investment, competition and the environment. These issues have particular human development implications for developing countries. Often the BTAs/RTAs have requirements that are \u201cWTO-plus,\u201d or rights and obligations that go beyond what is required in the multilateral forum. This emerging trend, to negotiate international trade outside the multilateral framework, makes it clear that developing countries must build awareness about the commitments and safeguard their development interests. - 5 - 1. BOUQUETS AND BRICKBATS Advantages from the GATT/WTO system Why are developing countries in the WTO, and why is there such a rush to join it? Some important reasons are the following: First, developing countries need to export because (i) they need foreign exchange to pay for their essential imports, like fuel, technology, capital goods, industrial inputs and food, and (ii) they need markets in other countries for their goods and services to expand their production, employment and pro\ufb01t. However, their goods and services cannot automatically enter other countries; there has to be permission for entry. This permission, in turn, requires an agreement with other countries. Thus, to send exports to other countries a developing country will need to have bilateral agreements with all of them. Joining a multilateral framework, such as the WTO, where Member Countries have allowed the import and export of goods and services among themselves, obviates this procedure. It is also unlikely that a developing country will get a better deal in a bilateral agreement than what is possible in the multilateral framework. Recent experiences show that they have had to make a higher level of commitments in BTAs with developed countries than what is required in the WTO. Second, the mechanism for the enforcement of rights and obligations in the WTO, embodied in its dispute settlement system, provides some protection against the subjective actions of other countries. Yet the enforcement mechanism has many de\ufb01ciencies, as will be explained in following sections. Third, being a Member of the WTO community of countries gives a country the opportunity to learn from others\u2019 experiences and to in\ufb02uence the trade negotiating process, to some extent. Finally, because the GATT/WTO framework for conducting international trade has existed for nearly six decades, it is out of the ordinary for a country to remain outside it, and other countries may view this exclusion suspiciously. Problems in the GATT/WTO system Why are developing countries persistently complaining about this system? The basic problems are both structural and operational. Some important ones are explained below. Structural problems First, the framework has the basic objective to liberalize trade in goods and services and to protect intellectual property rights, to be explained in a later section. The former results in the expansion of exports and directly bene\ufb01ts countries with supply capacity. The latter gives monopoly privileges, including high \ufb01nancial returns, to the owners of intellectual property rights (IPR), thus bene\ufb01ting the countries that own intellectual property. Most developing countries have neither a good supply base for goods and services, nor own much intellectual property. As a result, their direct gains are comparatively smaller than those of developed countries. Second, the basis for liberalization is reciprocity. If a country is able to give more, it gets more. Conversely, if it gives less, it also gets less. Such a system is appropriate for countries at a similar level of economic development. Problems arise when Members - 6 - have vastly diverse economic levels. In such a situation, there is built-in bias in a system that increases disparities among countries. Some correctives have been attempted from time to time, such as differential and more favourable treatment of developing countries, but none of these initiatives have worked satisfactorily. Third, the ultimate weapon for enforcing Members\u2019 rights is through retaliation, as will be explained in the chapter on Enforcement Mechanism. This enforcement may be most appropriate in a system where Members have similar strength. In the GATT/WTO system it puts developing countries that are the weaker partners at a further disadvantage. For them, retaliation against a major developed country has both economic and political costs. Therefore, their capacity to enforce their rights and obligations is constrained. Finally, certain basic principles and provisions in this system operate against development efforts, at least in the short term. For example, a basic principle in the GATT is national treatment, i.e., non-discrimination between an imported product and a similar domestic product, to be explained in detail later in the chapter on Trade in Goods. In the process of development, a country may prefer to encourage the production and use of a domestic product, but it is", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2c8029f4-abc1-471a-b43c-dfb9b2c101b3": {"__data__": {"id_": "2c8029f4-abc1-471a-b43c-dfb9b2c101b3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "69901bdb0c816c020ffba5dae6563a4ca9dbaacd236a56c26009b1a9271fa3ff"}, "3": {"node_id": "fbaff089-1eef-4684-88e1-2f4d5f94f5b6", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "637c2c14e191b54451e67ad25a1bd0bda88edc4f3d287eb7e7d64a56f5b9b84f"}}, "hash": "4aeef5759882eaa749a0181f0b358349785043171e112ffdf878294e94707df9", "text": "prohibited through the principle of national treatment. Operational problems First, the decision-making process in the WTO system is dominated by developed countries, as explained in detail in the chapter on the WTO Process. Their objectives are clear and strategies focused. They have technical and \ufb01nancial resources to prepare well, in order to put forth their points of view strongly and effectively in the negotiations; often they become the driving force in the negotiations. Thus, the subjects of their economic and political interest come to centre stage, resulting in decisions aligned with their agendas. These norms often cause frustration among developing countries. Substantial negotiations often are conducted in small groups where most developing countries are not present, which will be explained later in the chapter on the WTO Process. Then the results are brought to the larger group -- and Members that have not participated are expected to agree. Developing countries, even though they may not be in full agreement, \ufb01nd it dif\ufb01cult to stop the decision at that stage because such a move will cast them as obstructionists, with political costs. Hence, developing countries generally keep quiet, but the imbalanced negotiating process continues, adding to their burden of obligations and increasing their dissatisfaction. Sometimes there are loopholes in WTO agreements, which developed countries often use to their advantage. For example, the major developed countries ful\ufb01lled their obligation of reducing their domestic subsidy in strict technical sense, but, in actual practice, they increased the total quantum of their domestic subsidy. This has been possible because the Agreement on Agriculture (AOA) stipulates that some subsidies are immune from reduction. Moreover, in the textiles and clothing (T&C) sector, developed countries ful\ufb01lled their obligation of liberalization, but, in effect, only very partial liberalization occurred for nearly 10 years under the implementation of Agreement on Textiles and Clothing (ATC). The ATC left the choice of products to the importing countries; developed countries that were importers and had been imposing restraints chose only such products for liberalization that were not under import restraint. They ful\ufb01lled their obligation without signi\ufb01cantly liberalizing their textile imports until the end of 2004, when all restraints were automatically abolished \u2013 making the ATC an \u201cend-loaded\u201d process. - 7 - Finally, in general, developing countries believe that the GATT/WTO process is about extracting concessions from them, and that it constrains their development space and options. Naturally, it generates tension in the system. - 8 - 2. STRUCTURE AND COVERAGE OF THE WTO Structure Originally, the WTO was formulated as the GATT in 1947. The United States and the United Kingdom were the main architects, though there were 23 members in the beginning, of which 12 were those that are now called developing countries. The GATT was essentially a framework for reducing tariffs (or customs duty) until 1979. At this time, certain disciplines were ampli\ufb01ed in the non- tariff areas, such as subsidies given by governments, dumping by \ufb01rms, licensing in the case of import control, and valuation of customs duty at the time of import of a product. As a result of the Uruguay Round of negotiations (1986-94), the WTO was created on 1 January 1995 and the GATT became part of it. The WTO is a multilateral framework (an agreement among governments) for the conduct of international trade in goods and services and also for the protection of intellectual property rights, such as patents, copyrights and trademarks. The WTO has a set of multilateral agreements, primarily on the rights and obligations of governments that prescribe disciplines in the formulation of rules, procedures and practices in these areas. In a limited way, it also provides disciplines on \ufb01rms, for example, by restraining them from exporting products at abnormally low prices (considered dumping). But it is only governments that participate in the negotiations, in the formulation of agreements, and in raising disputes against one another regarding the enforcement of provisions of the agreements. Coverage The WTO disciplines are in three parts: (i) for trade in goods, contained in the GATT, and in some other agreements on goods (ii) for trade in services, contained in the General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS); and (iii) for protection of intellectual property rights, contained in the Agreement on Trade- Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (Agreement on TRIPS).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fbaff089-1eef-4684-88e1-2f4d5f94f5b6": {"__data__": {"id_": "fbaff089-1eef-4684-88e1-2f4d5f94f5b6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "69901bdb0c816c020ffba5dae6563a4ca9dbaacd236a56c26009b1a9271fa3ff"}, "2": {"node_id": "2c8029f4-abc1-471a-b43c-dfb9b2c101b3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4aeef5759882eaa749a0181f0b358349785043171e112ffdf878294e94707df9"}}, "hash": "637c2c14e191b54451e67ad25a1bd0bda88edc4f3d287eb7e7d64a56f5b9b84f", "text": "There is an agreement called the Dispute Settlement Understanding (DSU) for the enforcement of the rights and obligations and for resolving disputes between governments in the areas covered by these agreements. Ensemble of agreements Goods The old GATT, mentioned above, is now technically called GATT 1947. GATT 1947 and some Understandings reached in some areas of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "086e8831-d75e-419c-8b13-5a94afb85c51": {"__data__": {"id_": "086e8831-d75e-419c-8b13-5a94afb85c51", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "be440b1078f5800e1640d0b89c49ba0c97a1a138ef11503825949b02f2908f84"}, "3": {"node_id": "fa51964b-bb07-40df-ac81-98cfbfba500f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e1d6f73ddd9d774925f4e6b164304231d1d3ccef21406162703ba3d41d1b7607"}}, "hash": "9d33695019696cedb38b08973102ae70ad0ca028fee6c2f95b8be7be55374825", "text": "the goods sector in the Uruguay Round are together called GATT 1994. The Uruguay Round formulated a set of additional comprehensive agreements on the subjects of agriculture, sanitary and phyto-sanitary (SPS) measures, textiles and clothing, technical barriers to trade, trade- related investment measures, anti-dumping, customs valuations, pre-shipment inspection, rules of origin (ROO), import licensing, subsidies and safeguards. These agreements (and GATT 1994) together form the comprehensive disciplines in the area of goods. The provisions of these new agreements override those of the GATT 1994, in case of con\ufb02ict. Services GATS contains the disciplines in the area of services. IPR The Agreement on TRIPS contains the disciplines in the area of protection of intellectual property rights. - 9 - Dispute settlement The Dispute Settlement Understanding provides the framework and procedure for settlement of disputes between Members on the enforcement of rights and obligations contained in the agreements listed above. These four sets of agreements are in the form of annexes to the main agreement that created the WTO. It is titled: \u201cMarrakesh Agreement Establishing the World Trade Organization,\u201d in short \u201cWTO Agreement.\u201d All these texts are compiled in one place in the WTO publication, \u201cThe Results of the Uruguay Round of Multilateral Trade Negotiations: The Legal Texts.\u201d Institutions The highest decision-making body in the WTO is the Ministerial Conference that meets at least once in two years. So far, these conferences have been held in Singapore (1996), Geneva (1998), Seattle (1999), Doha (2001), Cancun (2003) and Hong Kong (2005). In the period between two Ministerial Conferences, the General Council is empowered to discharge the functions of the Ministerial Conference. There are councils for speci\ufb01c areas: Council for Trade in Goods, for the implementation of agreements on goods; Council for Trade in Services, for implementation of the GATS; and Council for TRIPS, for implementation of the Agreement on TRIPS. The Dispute Settlement Body (DSB) operates the DSU. All Members of the WTO are members of all these bodies. Decision-making process Decisions are generally taken in the WTO by consensus, which has been speci\ufb01cally de\ufb01ned. A decision will be deemed as to be based on consensus \u201cif no Member, present at the meeting when the decision is being taken, formally objects to the proposed decision.\u201d If consensus is not possible, the decision is taken by voting. There is a system of \u2018one Member, one vote\u2019 and decisions are made generally by majority vote. For very special purposes, higher majority is prescribed. For example, a decision on the interpretation of an agreement or on waivers of an obligation needs a three-fourths majority. Amendments require two-thirds majority, or in some matters, acceptance by all Members. In actual practice, Members seldom resort to voting; differences are settled by prolonged consultations and discussions. - 10 - 3. TRADE IN GOODS Basic principles The most basic principle in the GATT/WTO system is that there should be free and open competition in trade. Toward this end, two provisions form the main pillars of the system: most favoured nation treatment and national treatment, as explained below. Most Favoured Nation (MFN) treatment This provides that there must not be any discrimination between different Member countries in the manner of treatment that a Member extends to them. (The title is derived from the fact that any concession given by a country to the most favoured country also has to be extended to all members of the WTO). There are two examples: \ufffd If a country wants to give lower tariffs on a product to another country as a reward for receiving aid or investment, it will be violating the MFN principle. \ufffd A country cannot express displeasure to another country for voting against it in the UN by stopping imports from that country or by introducing an especially cumbersome custom clearance process for goods from that country. All tariffs and import rules have to be non-discriminatory between various countries that are Members of the WTO. There are some exceptions to the MFN rule. For example, two countries or a group of countries may form regional trading arrangements and may extend lower tariffs to one another without giving this bene\ufb01t to those outside the arrangement.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fa51964b-bb07-40df-ac81-98cfbfba500f": {"__data__": {"id_": "fa51964b-bb07-40df-ac81-98cfbfba500f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "be440b1078f5800e1640d0b89c49ba0c97a1a138ef11503825949b02f2908f84"}, "2": {"node_id": "086e8831-d75e-419c-8b13-5a94afb85c51", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9d33695019696cedb38b08973102ae70ad0ca028fee6c2f95b8be7be55374825"}}, "hash": "e1d6f73ddd9d774925f4e6b164304231d1d3ccef21406162703ba3d41d1b7607", "text": "In addition, developing countries may get special bene\ufb01ts from other countries, and they may have special arrangements among themselves without others getting the bene\ufb01ts. National treatment This is the principle of non-discrimination between an imported product and a similar domestic product. A country is prohibited from providing less favourable treatment to an imported product than provided to a similar domestic product. An exception to national treatment is to have a provision of a subsidy for the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fd3e9804-29de-448e-8199-b560a71caba4": {"__data__": {"id_": "fd3e9804-29de-448e-8199-b560a71caba4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2e7c686922c09f85d3303102a9a37e816e0ee624e01d571ab249897f38688346"}}, "hash": "2e7c686922c09f85d3303102a9a37e816e0ee624e01d571ab249897f38688346", "text": "production of domestic products under certain disciplines without providing such a subsidy to the similar imported product. Tariffs In general, goods exported from one country to another country must be allowed unrestrained entry into the latter. However, a country may apply tariffs, i.e., customs duty, on a product at the time of import. Tariffs have three functions: (i) they provide revenue to the government; (ii) they protect domestic products from competition with imported products, as the latter becomes more costly due to tariffs; and (iii) they are instruments in development policy for discouraging non-priority imports, such as luxury goods, while encouraging priority imports like capital goods and industrial inputs. When a country undertakes obligations in the WTO to \u201cbind\u201d a tariff on a product, it cannot raise the tariff on that product beyond the \u201cbound\u201d level. It may apply a lower tariff at its own discretion. If a country has not \u201cbound\u201d the tariff on a particular product, it is free to put any level of tariff on it. The bound levels for a country - 11 - are included in that country\u2019s tariff schedule, which is kept in the WTO for the record. Because the imported product becomes more costly when a tariff is levied than without it, the tariff has a restraining effect on the import. A country cannot apply any other restraint on the import, except in speci\ufb01c cases, as explained below. Contingency protection There are some speci\ufb01c situations in which a country may restrict imports: Safeguards If the domestic industry of a country suffers serious injury because of increased imports or if there is even a threat of serious injury, the country may put restrictions on imports, either by raising the import duty or by putting quantitative restrictions on the import. A safeguard action must be taken on the import as a whole, not against the import from a particular country. Thus, if an additional tariff is applied as a safeguard measure, it will be applicable to imports from all sources. If quantitative restrictions are applied, an annual limit of imports will be \ufb01xed, based on past imports and then this quantity will be allocated to all the countries generally in proportion to past imports. A safeguard measure is a temporary measure. It can continue only so long as the injury continues. Generally, the maximum duration to apply a safeguard measure is four years. In certain circumstances, it can be extended, but the total maximum period must not exceed eight years. When a country applies a safeguard measure, it has to give compensatory bene\ufb01t to countries that have substantial interest in the export of that product. In absence of compensation, those countries can take retaliatory measures (usually in the form of raising the tariffs on some products of that country). But no retaliatory measure can generally be taken during the \ufb01rst three years of the safeguard measure. Balance of Payment Provision When a country has balance of payment problems (which is the problem of small foreign exchange reserves and low net in\ufb02ows) it may put restrictions on imports by either raising the import duty or by putting quantitative restrictions on imports. Under this provision, restrictions have to be applied to imports of selected products from all sources. A country cannot use this provision to restrict imports of products only from a particular country. General exceptions Imports from a particular country can be stopped under certain conditions that are covered by the general exceptions in the GATT 1994. For example, a country may restrain imports for reasons to protect public morals (e.g., books and magazines considered indecent), to protect life and health of human beings, animals and plants (e.g., injurious food articles or those with improper packaging), and to protect the environment. Relief against unfair trade There are provisions for relief against unfair trade. Two situations of unfair trade have been identi\ufb01ed: (i) subsidy, i.e., bene\ufb01ts given by the government for production or export and (ii) dumping, i.e., export of a product by a \ufb01rm at abnormally low prices. The underlying principle is that products should be able to compete in international markets on their own, without major support from the government. Similarly, prices should not be made arti\ufb01cially low to eliminate competition; for example, a \ufb01rm should generally not export products at prices below the cost of - 12 - production. The agreements on subsidies and anti-dumping are very elaborate and have given rise to a large number of disputes in the WTO. Subsidies Some types of subsidies are totally prohibited. These are: export subsidies and import substitution subsidies, i.e., subsidies given for the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "52db7a5c-894c-4ca1-8a27-90ee248872a5": {"__data__": {"id_": "52db7a5c-894c-4ca1-8a27-90ee248872a5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b802cf03799c7b3f3edaef2986abf65709bbbd5fcfdf314d06628ef752724e70"}}, "hash": "b802cf03799c7b3f3edaef2986abf65709bbbd5fcfdf314d06628ef752724e70", "text": "use of domestic products in preference to imported products. The Least Developed Countries (LDCs) and other developing countries that have gross national product (GNP) per capita of less than US$ 1,000 per annum are exempted from the prohibition of export subsidies. The prohibition on import substitution subsidies has applied to the LDCs since the end of 2002 and to other developing countries since the end of 1999. One category of domestic subsidy given for production is permitted. This is what is called non-speci\ufb01c or general subsidies, i.e., the subsidies given for production across the board to the entire industrial sector, based on some generally applied criteria. For example, subsidies without any restrictions can be given to small \ufb01rms, based on the criteria of the maximum number of employees or maximum annual value of outputs, applicable to all industrial sectors. Speci\ufb01c subsidies, i.e., subsidies given for domestic production in a speci\ufb01c industrial sector (there are separate provisions for agriculture) or to speci\ufb01c industrial \ufb01rms, have been put under discipline. In practice, such subsidies can continue until some country protests and raises a dispute. Such a situation can emerge if the subsidies are: (i) causing material injury or threatening to cause material injury to the industry of another country or (ii) causing serious prejudice to the industry of another country. The factors for determining injury include declines in output, sale, price, pro\ufb01t, return on investment, capacity utilization, employment and wages. The factors for determining serious prejudice are somewhat less stringent. These include displacing or impeding the import in the subsidizing country, displacing or impeding the export in a third-country market, and price undercutting. In case material injury or its threat exists, a country may impose countervailing duties on the subsidized product to compensate for the effect of a subsidy. Or a country may take to the dispute settlement route and have the subsidy removed. Elaborate rules have been prescribed for determining injury and the quantum of subsidization, which have been the subject of many disputes in the WTO. In case of existence of serious prejudice, there is only one route of relief; a country may resort to the dispute settlement process to have the subsidy removed. Anti-dumping Dumping is said to exist if the export price of a product is less than what is called the normal value, which is generally the price of the product in the exporting country. If the price in the exporting country is not possible to determine or if the comparison is not possible, there are alternative methods for determining the normal value. It may be taken as the price of the product when exported to a third country. Alternatively, it may be constructed on the basis of the cost of production plus a reasonable amount for pro\ufb01t and associated expenses. Again, like a subsidy, it has to be ascertained that there is material injury or threat of material injury to the domestic production. If it is established that injury is caused or threatened by the dumped import, an anti-dumping duty may be imposed. This process has been the subject of several disputes in the WTO. - 13 - Standards A country has the right to specify standards for products. Of course, the main condition is that the principles of MFN and national treatment will apply in this case. Hence, the standard has to be applied to the product from all countries as well as to the domestic product. There is an agreement on this subject in the WTO called Agreement on the Technical Barriers to Trade. Setting standards and applying them has to conform to the process prescribed in this agreement. Preference is given to the standards set by international institutions. Therefore, it is desirable for developing countries to participate in these institutions in formulating standards; otherwise, the standards may be set without keeping the situations of these countries in view. Procedural provisions There are rules in the WTO on procedural provisions, such as customs valuation, licensing in the case of monitoring or restraining imports (whenever import restraint is permitted), and operation of state trading enterprises. Negotiations are on-going in the area of trade facilitation, covering the processes of customs clearance, transit of goods and noti\ufb01cation. This area is one of four subjects among the \u201cSingapore issues\u201d (to be discussed in detail in the chapter on New Issues) that has been taken up in the current negotiations. Agriculture The general disciplines of the GATT/WTO apply to all sectors except agriculture. Earlier, the textiles sector also was covered by a special regime of rules, but since the beginning of 2005 it has been brought under", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "546db523-c42d-4dda-b425-5781819b366c": {"__data__": {"id_": "546db523-c42d-4dda-b425-5781819b366c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4509e7372d36bea8ef5e94c647abb45dcbb2bcee52c3850f45a03eda21692642"}}, "hash": "4509e7372d36bea8ef5e94c647abb45dcbb2bcee52c3850f45a03eda21692642", "text": "the fold of the general disciplines. Agriculture remained under a soft discipline in the GATT system right from the beginning. Efforts had been going on for a long time in order to work out a set of new rules in this area, but it proved dif\ufb01cult. Finally, an agreement was concluded in the Uruguay Round, and agriculture came within the special discipline of the Agreement on Agriculture (AOA) since the beginning of 1995. The disciplines are broadly covered in three areas: market access, domestic subsidies (termed as domestic support in the agreement) and export subsidies. Three points in the area of market access are important. First, all quantitative restrictions were abolished with the advent of WTO at the beginning of 1995. Second, the tariffs on some products are very high - - sometimes even as high as 200-300 percent -and thus prohibitive. Third, there is a special safeguard process (SSG) under which domestic production can be protected by additional tariffs even without proving injury. But the criteria for applying SSG are such that developing countries, except a few, cannot use it. The subject of domestic subsidies in agriculture has become a matter of major concern in the WTO. Developed countries are using it in large measures; and they are hesitant to eliminate it. Broadly, there are three types of domestic subsidies in agriculture, commonly described as being in the amber box, blue box and green box. (These terms came into use during the Uruguay Round negotiations and have continued since then. However, they have not been used in the AOA and thus do not have any formal and technical standing). These boxes are explained below. \u201cAmber Box\u201d subsidies are the domestic subsidies covered by Article 6.2 of the WTO Agreement on Agriculture, technically called the Aggregate Measurement of Support (AMS). They are measured - 14 - mainly in terms of the difference between the domestic price and the international price; they are subject to reduction. \u201cBlue Box\u201d subsidies are the domestic subsidies covered by Article 6.5 of the AOA. They are a direct payment to producers based on area/yield, and not subject to reduction in the AOA at present. \u201cGreen Box\u201d subsidies are the domestic subsidies covered by Annex 2 of the AOA. They include various types of direct payments to producers; they are not subject to reduction. There are proposals in the most recent negotiations to reduce the blue box subsidy and to clarify criteria for the green box. Moreover, it is also important to know two other terms that are frequently used in connection with the domestic subsidies in agriculture as follows. De-minimis subsidy: for product speci\ufb01c subsidy in the developed countries, it is 5 percent of the production of that product and, in addition, for non-product speci\ufb01c subsidy, it is further 5 percent of total agricultural production. For the developing countries, it is 10 percent of both. Trade-distorting subsidy: it is the total of amber box, blue box and de-minimis subsidies. Developed countries have been providing a huge subsidy to their own agriculture through these three boxes. Amber box subsidies are subject to reductions in the AOA but blue box and green box subsidies are immune from reduction. The major developed countries ful\ufb01lled their obligation of reducing amber box subsidies, but raised the amounts in the other two boxes, thus retaining their subsidy levels and even increasing them. This \u201cbox shifting\u201d by the major developed countries has caused great worry to developing countries. Green box subsidies are not subjected to the discipline of reduction in the AOA because they are seen as non- trade-distorting. Yet this is not quite a correct premise. The green box has several components like subsidies for research, food aid, income insurance, crop insurance, investment aid, and structural adjustment assistance for taking away resources from agriculture. It also includes direct payment to farmers simply as support that is de- coupled from production and price. Many of these payments, particularly direct payment support, insurance against income loss and investment aid enhance the staying capacity of farmers in their agricultural production that is considered unviable. In this manner, it distorts production and trade, hence, the presumption that the green box subsidies are non-trade-distorting is not correct. Blue box subsidies were carved out in the Uruguay Round mainly to accommodate the European Union, and even though they were acknowledged to be trade-distorting, no reduction was envisaged. It was expected that the EU would reduce blue box subsidies and \ufb01nally eliminate them. In fact, the United States removed its own blue box subsidies. However, the EU did not eliminate its blue box subsidies, and the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cabce71b-a4df-4f28-9f19-3bc5ed6691b9": {"__data__": {"id_": "cabce71b-a4df-4f28-9f19-3bc5ed6691b9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "95001026f0bcaa9a32296ca92f2b40de038747f420a25a61f89a2f369367a477"}}, "hash": "95001026f0bcaa9a32296ca92f2b40de038747f420a25a61f89a2f369367a477", "text": "US reconsidered its position and thought of reinstituting them. These subsidies are helping the EU and US to export their agriculture and to protect their farmers against imports. Other developed countries like Japan, Switzerland and Norway also use domestic subsidies in high proportion to their production, thereby protecting their farmers against imports. But they do not export their agricultural products, so they do not put the farmers of other countries at risk of losing their income and livelihoods. All these practices will be explained in more detail in the chapter on Main Issues at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference. Major developed countries also use export subsidies in agriculture. The main user of export subsidies in the form of direct payment is the European Union. The US - 15 - uses export subsidies mainly through export credits and food aid. Hong Kong Ministerial Conference has decided to remove export subsidies by 2013. Implications for developing countries in all these areas and currently con\ufb02icting interests will be discussed in the chapter on Main Issues at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference. Opportunities and risks for developing countries Up to the mid-1980s, there was no serious demand on developing countries in the GATT system to undertake obligations. The exercise of exchanging concessions was mostly limited to developed countries. However, through the operation of the MFN clause, explained earlier, the bene\ufb01t also was available to developing countries that were members of the GATT system. Two points are noted in this connection. Through the exercise of mutual concessions, developed countries reduced their tariffs on products of their mutual interests, thus leaving tariffs on products of interest to the developing countries at comparatively high levels. For example, their average tariff is now quite low, nearly 4 percent; but within this average they have tariffs as high as 15-30 percent, which are generally placed on products of interest to developing countries, such as textiles and clothing, food processing and footwear. The challenge for developing countries in the current negotiations is to get the tariff peaks and high tariffs. Developing countries got the bene\ufb01t of lower tariffs on several products and some countries used it to their advantage, by improving their exports and share in international trade. Yet it was not totally a one-sided bene\ufb01t. As countries rose on the development ladder, they provided opportunities for developed countries to expand their markets in these countries. Developing countries absorbed a signi\ufb01cant part of increased production in developed countries. This process has been a mutual gain for developed countries and developing countries that utilized the lower tariffs. It must be noted that a large number of developing countries have not been able to derive bene\ufb01ts from lower tariffs due to their weak supply capacity in these products. From an economic development angle there is concern that some provisions of the agreements in the area of goods are not conducive to development. For example, the principle of national treatment prohibits special facilities for domestic products that face competition from imported products that often are backed by massive resources from \ufb01rms in developed countries. It hampers the development of domestic production. Furthermore, foreign exchange balancing is not permitted; thus, a country cannot stipulate that imports by a \ufb01rm should be \ufb01nanced, at least in part, by the export of its products. This rule may constrain the development process when foreign exchange is scarce. Developing countries also face various forms of protectionism in developed countries. As tariffs in those countries were lowered, protection began through quantitative restrictions on imports. Many sectors of interest to developing countries were seriously affected in this manner. The main examples include textiles, leather goods and jute goods. Quantitative restrictions were \ufb01nally eliminated in the Uruguay Round. Then developed countries applied other methods of protection, e.g., anti- dumping processes. A large number of anti- dumping investigations against exports from developing countries commenced in several major developed countries. Sometimes no injury or dumping was found in the enquiry and the anti-dumping process was dropped. However, the damage already was caused because of uncertainties created by the anti- dumping investigation. - 16 - Sometimes, developed countries would resort to repeatedly launching investigations on a particular product, which would, in effect, harm prospects for developing countries to export it. Exports from developing countries also were stopped sometimes on grounds of safeguarding the environment. In several cases, dispute settlement panels in the WTO found these restrictions illegal. These techniques of neo- protectionism in developed countries have been the cause of major concern among the developing countries. At the same time, risks arise with pressures from developed countries for the drastic reduction in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9bb9c246-9990-492d-9eac-f4154ca7e498": {"__data__": {"id_": "9bb9c246-9990-492d-9eac-f4154ca7e498", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "19b67233219502bce6dce2d51c53741a99bfee616c6885ae714bd66768061746"}, "3": {"node_id": "c91bc808-f8b1-46fc-b519-26f8cdf624db", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ad5017d3c6a7648274686f489aa7924ead0cc900d2877dc19b8fb6b5e7168908"}}, "hash": "adba9d45b16a0313a6db795d71903d1712300fcd3642869ee9dbb592e1b42f1b", "text": "tariffs of developing countries. The option for using quantitative import controls already has been much curtailed; thus, now the only protection for the domestic industry is through tariffs. If tariffs are bound at low levels, as demanded by developed countries, the process of industrialization in developing countries may suffer. If developing countries take a binding commitment to quickly lower their tariffs on a large scale, they may lose the opportunity to move up on the scale of higher technological production. Then there is risk in the agriculture sector. Developing countries are under pressure to lower their tariffs, whereas developed countries are not prepared to eliminate their own domestic subsidies. This imbalance will leave the farmers in developing countries in a vastly disadvantaged position, thereby threatening their income and livelihood. These issues are to be handled prudently in the current negotiations. A more detailed account will be given in the chapter on Main Issues at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference. - 17 - 4. TRADE IN SERVICES Background The services sector is covered under GATS. This subject entered the multilateral trading system in the beginning of 1995 as a result of the completion of GATS in the Uruguay Round. Developed countries initiated the agreement, expecting signi\ufb01cant bene\ufb01ts to their economies by the liberalization of services sectors in all countries, particularly the developing countries. They were being pushed to liberalize services by various pressure groups, particularly the \ufb01nancial services. The GATS is centred on the liberalization of services, which entails curtailing the functions of government that regulate the entry and operation of foreign services and service providers in the country. There are two broad categories of obligations on liberalization. First, general obligations, applied to all service sectors: for example, the principle of non-discrimination, Most Favoured Nation treatment (MFN), explained in the chapter on Trade in Goods; and rules regarding the recognition of quali\ufb01cations and standards. Second, speci\ufb01c commitments of liberalization in speci\ufb01c services sectors apply. Modes of supply The obligations on speci\ufb01c sectoral commitments are in terms of the modes of supply of service. Four modes of supply have been envisaged. Because there are frequent references to these modes of supply when talking about services negotiations or commitments, it is important to be familiar with their content. The four modes of supply of service are: Mode 1: Supply of service from one country to another country; for example, supplying a software programme or an engineering design of a machine by a person/\ufb01rm from one country to a person/\ufb01rm in another country; Mode 2: Provision of service in a country to the consumer of another country; for example, providing medical treatment in a country to a person of another country; Mode 3: Supply of service by the service supplier of one country to another country through commercial presence in that country; for example, supplying \ufb01nancial service through a banking \ufb01rm by opening a branch in another country; Mode 4: Supply of service by one country to another country through presence of natural persons there; for example, providing advice or repairing a machine in another country by an expert travelling to that country. In short, these four modes are described in the WTO respectively as: i) cross-border supply, ii) consumption abroad, iii) commercial presence and iv) presence of natural persons. The term \u201cnatural persons\u201d refers to men/women workers of a country, as distinguished from the \u201cjuridical person,\u201d which means a legal entity like a company or \ufb01rm. Speci\ufb01c sectoral commitment Under a speci\ufb01c sectoral commitment a country undertakes the obligation to allow the provision of service in a particular sector by a foreign service provider. A country chooses the sectors in which to allow imports, i.e., the provision of service by a foreign supplier. The choice is technically with the country that makes it, but in actual practice, countries enter into negotiations to persuade one another to liberalize their respective service sectors. The \ufb01nal result - 18 - of such negotiations comes in the form of commitments of different countries in different sectors. While agreeing to include a sector in its commitment to liberalize, a country may prescribe some conditions and limitations on market access and national treatment (this term has been explained in the chapter on Trade in Goods). If no condition or limitation is laid down at the time of taking commitment, the presumption is that the country has allowed totally unrestrained liberalization in that sector.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c91bc808-f8b1-46fc-b519-26f8cdf624db": {"__data__": {"id_": "c91bc808-f8b1-46fc-b519-26f8cdf624db", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "19b67233219502bce6dce2d51c53741a99bfee616c6885ae714bd66768061746"}, "2": {"node_id": "9bb9c246-9990-492d-9eac-f4154ca7e498", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "adba9d45b16a0313a6db795d71903d1712300fcd3642869ee9dbb592e1b42f1b"}}, "hash": "ad5017d3c6a7648274686f489aa7924ead0cc900d2877dc19b8fb6b5e7168908", "text": "The sectors covered by the commitment of liberalization, along with any conditions and limitations, are inscribed in the services schedule of the Member, which is preserved in the WTO as record of commitment. Most", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1b4a6574-5bb1-45ae-94c0-169943267e5c": {"__data__": {"id_": "1b4a6574-5bb1-45ae-94c0-169943267e5c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1e1acf5c46645f1942d0057c8ded4ee74ed8044834079f84f44e8754f9f562bc"}}, "hash": "1e1acf5c46645f1942d0057c8ded4ee74ed8044834079f84f44e8754f9f562bc", "text": "recent negotiations The GATS envisages progressive liberalization in services sectors through negotiations from time to time. The \ufb01rst set of negotiations took place during the Uruguay Round. Now another round of negotiation is going on since 2001, for which Guidelines and procedures were formulated in March 2001. The negotiations are being conducted mostly on the basis of what is called the \u201crequest- offer\u201d approach. Countries have given requests to one another specifying sectors in which there should be liberalization, as well as the transactions that need to be liberalized. In addition, countries have given offers to one another that mention where and how much they are willing to liberalize. Further negotiations on the basis of requests and offers will continue. Naturally, a country will try to persuade another to improve its offers, which will be the subject of negotiation. Since the Hong Kong Ministerial Declaration, a parallel track of negotiation through a plurilateral route has assumed prominence. Many developing countries do not perceive good prospects for themselves in terms of liberalizing services by other countries because they do not have adequate supply capacity to export services. Therefore, they have not considered it necessary to make many offers. The major developed countries would like all countries, including developing countries, to undertake at least minimum liberalization commitments. They have presented proposals under various titles, like a benchmark for commitments and a numerical target for commitments, which they propose should be applicable to all countries. This pressure has created controversy and tension in services negotiations and will be discussed in detail in the chapter on Main Issues at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference. Currently, negotiations are also underway to formulate rules on subsidies, safeguards and government procurement. Developing countries are keen to work out an effective safeguard mechanism so that the import of services can be stopped if domestic service supply is threatened by the import. In addition, they want to retain the option to subsidize their services sectors; hence, they are more interested in completing negotiations in these two areas. On the other hand, the major developed countries are interested in ensuring expansion of markets for their services with regard to the services purchased by governments in developing countries for the use of government. Therefore, they are keen to advance negotiations in the area of government procurement. Developing-countries provisions There are two speci\ufb01c provisions regarding special treatment of developing countries in the GATS: First, the increasing participation of developing countries in the services trade - 19 - shall be facilitated by commitments relating to strengthening their domestic supply capacity, improving access to distribution channels, and liberalizing markets in sectors and modes that are of interest to them. Second, in the negotiations for speci\ufb01c sectoral commitments, there shall be appropriate \ufb02exibilities for an individual developing country to open fewer sectors and to liberalize fewer types of transactions. However, it is often observed, that these provisions are ignored by the major developed countries, while they continue to make demands on developing countries in the negotiations. Opportunities and risks for developing countries Since the GATS is about liberalizing the entry of foreign services in a country, the direct bene\ufb01ts from it go to those countries that have developed supply capacity in the services sectors. The agreement is very much unbalanced in terms of bene\ufb01ts. Imbalances increase when sectors that have been prioritized in the negotiations, such as \ufb01nancial and telecommunication services, show supply capacity almost exclusively in developed countries. Even if some developing countries have some supply capacity in several sectors, developed countries have problems with recognizing standards and quali\ufb01cations. They would allow only such services and service providers that conform to their standards and quali\ufb01cations, which are quite high, and sometimes unaffordable for developing countries to attain. Many developed countries have concluded mutual recognition agreements among themselves, through which they recognize each other\u2019s standards and quali\ufb01cations -- but developing countries are mostly left out of these recognition agreements. This understanding among developed countries can be an additional hurdle in developing countries\u2019 services export. Developing countries would have bene\ufb01ted to some extent from liberalization of Mode 4 of supply of service, i.e., supply of service by the presence of natural persons. But developed countries have not been forthcoming with their commitments for liberalization in this area. There is a need for adequate correctives to redress this imbalance. As will be explained in detail in the chapter on the Main Issues at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference, the major developed countries are engaged more in putting pressures on developing countries for further concessions, rather than focusing on redressing the current imbalances in the services", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e8186799-5108-41eb-aa89-08ffd0702888": {"__data__": {"id_": "e8186799-5108-41eb-aa89-08ffd0702888", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bfc5fd8bde03d03f6cf02e7ca21d8211b24e410d8375616472ade0d3286493e2"}}, "hash": "bfc5fd8bde03d03f6cf02e7ca21d8211b24e410d8375616472ade0d3286493e2", "text": "sector. Furthermore, the risk for developing countries is that several signi\ufb01cant sectors, such as education, water supply and public health, may get covered by the obligations and governments may lose their primary role in these sectors. It is important for the developing countries to guard against this danger. - 20 - 5. PROTECTION OF INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RIGHTS Background Intellectual property rights like services, is another area that was brought into the multilateral trading system at the insistence of major developed countries, propelled mainly by their pharmaceutical sector. The subject of IPR is very much different from trade. In addition, it is about the protection of monopoly control on intellectual property and it is far removed from the principles of free trade, which form the basis of the WTO. Hence, it does not have a place in the WTO, yet remains in it at the insistence of major developed countries. Their main concern was that the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO), the multilateral organisation handling IPR did not have a proper enforcement mechanism and WIPO agreements\u2019 obligations were rather weak. They chose the WTO with an effective enforcement arm where they could impose the obligations on the developing countries that were their main targets, as the protection of IPR in the developed countries was already quite strong. The Agreement on TRIPS is the framework for IPR protection in the WTO. It lays down disciplines in seven areas of IPR: patent, copyright, trademark, Geographical Indications, industrial design, integrated circuits and undisclosed information. Of these, patent, copyright and Geographical Indications are the most important from the development angle. The need to protect IPR, which is to protect creations of the mind, arises from the notion that the inventor/creator must get adequate \ufb01nancial returns, which presumably provides incentives to innovate. Protection usually is in the form of exclusive rights for production, marketing and use. This raises the price which is borne by the consumer. There has to be a proper balance between the returns for an innovator and the cost to the consumer. A society determines this balance based on its own social, political and economic concepts and priorities. It is not imperative that all countries have the balance at the same level; however, the Agreement on TRIPS, by providing a minimum standard of protection on IPR, prescribes the base for that balance. Obligations for a country The Agreement on TRIPS provides the minimum level of protection on seven types of IPR that a country must have, but a country is free to have higher levels of protection. Because patents and copyrights have important implications for development, the treatment that follows will deal with them. Patent Eligibility for patent An invention is eligible for patent, if it is new, involves an inventive step (it is non-obvious), and is capable of industrial application (it is useful). If an application is made to register patent for an invention, a country has to enquire if it ful\ufb01ls all these conditions; then, if the conditions are ful\ufb01lled, it must register the patent at the national Patent Of\ufb01ce. Invention of both a product and a process can be patented. It is not obligatory for a country to register patents for: (i) diagnostic, therapeutic and surgical methods and (ii) plants and animals, and essentially biological processes for the production of plants and animals. However, a country may, if it wishes, include them in its patents registration system. It is not obligatory for a country to provide patent registration for - 21 - plant varieties, but it is obligatory to provide protection to it through what is called a sui generis system, meaning that a country may devise its own method to provide protection for plant varieties. A country may refuse a patent on the grounds of protection of: (i) public morality, (ii) human, animal or plant life or health and (iii) environment. The period of patent protection is at least 20 years from the date of \ufb01ling of the application for the patent. Rights of the patent owner In the case of a patent on a product, the IPR owner has the right to prevent anybody from producing, selling or importing the product without the consent of the IPR owner. For a patent on a process, the IPR owner has the right to prevent anybody from using the process without his/her consent; thus, it is necessary to obtain the owner\u2019s authorization for a product to be manufactured using that process. Compulsory license The government can give a license to a person to use a patent without the authorization of the IPR owner. This practice is called compulsory license", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ed2d5087-5918-427d-afc7-60631ba2f028": {"__data__": {"id_": "ed2d5087-5918-427d-afc7-60631ba2f028", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e28596607ee360539f7a21b54fdddd02697ebb8f20dd3864d07eb727ff0ee862"}, "3": {"node_id": "d9b84e88-fedc-4b20-a504-fd8d39687c7e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ef6139a63769deb48945457a70d6fa520378de34ed839d0afcc79e225d8757a9"}}, "hash": "4a10ba8947021a419243b15347637cfd02b634f4c35b36c614bd0c0c6a7e58f3", "text": "to distinguish it from the voluntary license given by the IPR owner. The Agreement on TRIPS does not prescribe the grounds on which compulsory license can be given by government; but it prescribes certain conditions, procedures and limitations regarding obtaining a compulsory license. One important condition is that the proposed user of the patent should have made efforts to get authorization from the IPR owner and prove that authorization could not be obtained within a reasonable period (the period is not de\ufb01ned in the Agreement). Also, the IPR owner has to be paid \u2018adequate\u2019 remuneration, which has not been speci\ufb01ed in the Agreement. Many provisions have not been speci\ufb01ed in the Agreement, so governments have the \ufb02exibility to prescribe them. Many countries have formulated legislation to incorporate their own provisions on these subjects. Copyright Copyrights cover protection of authors\u2019 rights in their literary and artistic works, as well as cinematographic works, works of architecture, computer programmes, compilation of data and the rights of performers, phonograms and broadcasting. The period of protection for a literary or artistic work or computer programme is for the life of the author and 50 years after his/her death. For cinematographic work, protection is for 50 years after the work has been made available to the public; for photographic work, it is 25 years from the making of the work; for performers and producers of phonograms, it is 50 years from the year of performance or \ufb01xation; and for broadcasting, it is 20 years from the end of the broadcast. While the patent is for a speci\ufb01c jurisdiction, such as in a country, the copyright is not limited in jurisdiction. The copyright applies to all countries. Furthermore, one does not have to apply for registration of copyright and receive registration, as in the case of patents. Copyright starts becoming applicable on its own after the work\u2019s creation, in accordance with the law of the respective country. Implementation Implementation of provisions within the Agreement on TRIPS has to be done by a country through appropriate legislation, rules and procedures. The Agreement prescribes detailed provisions on judicial processes and other aspects of implementation. - 22 - Risks for developing countries Because the TRIPS framework is for the protection of IPR and monopoly pro\ufb01ts for the IPR owner, direct bene\ufb01ts go to countries that have intellectual property. The IPR owners are mostly in the developed countries and very few in the developing countries. Thus the developed countries get most of the direct bene\ufb01ts from this framework. Some proponents for IPR state that a country would be able to strengthen its technological capacity by ensuring IPR protection. However, experiences of many countries have not shown such a conclusive relationship. On the other hand, there have been clear experiences showing the rise in prices of patented products. The effects -- notably the rising prices of medicines -- have been felt by a signi\ufb01cant number of developing countries. Many countries in the developing world are \ufb01nding it dif\ufb01cult to provide essential medicines to people at affordable prices. Because some countries allowed patenting of processes but not of products in the pharmaceutical sector, their scientists and technologists were able to produce the same products with alternative processes. As a result, they could supply generic medicines at much lower prices. But now these countries too are covered by obligations of product patents; hence, this alternative route of supply at cheaper prices is no longer available. Developing countries also have been the victims of biopiracy. Their plant resources have been appropriated by multinational \ufb01rms for further research, and these \ufb01rms have patented products derived from natural resources. Multinational corporations thus have derived monopoly pro\ufb01ts from developing countries\u2019 plant wealth, without sharing bene\ufb01ts with countries or communities that have nurtured these plants for centuries. The rationale that monopoly pro\ufb01ts provide incentives to invent should be reassessed. Rights over intellectual property have diverged from pure protection of creations of the mind into a path that is more focused on the protection of investment of multinational \ufb01rms that now dominate the \ufb01elds of science and technology. Hence, a new paradigm for protecting intellectual property rights may need to evolve, given this changed context. - 23 - 6. ENFORCEMENT MECHANISM Process and time frame Enforcement of the rules in the WTO is through the dispute settlement process contained in the Dispute Settlement Understanding.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d9b84e88-fedc-4b20-a504-fd8d39687c7e": {"__data__": {"id_": "d9b84e88-fedc-4b20-a504-fd8d39687c7e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e28596607ee360539f7a21b54fdddd02697ebb8f20dd3864d07eb727ff0ee862"}, "2": {"node_id": "ed2d5087-5918-427d-afc7-60631ba2f028", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4a10ba8947021a419243b15347637cfd02b634f4c35b36c614bd0c0c6a7e58f3"}}, "hash": "ef6139a63769deb48945457a70d6fa520378de34ed839d0afcc79e225d8757a9", "text": "The cause of action normally arises when a country perceives that any bene\ufb01t accruing as a result of commitments under an Agreement is being nulli\ufb01ed or impaired by an action of another country, or by a country\u2019s failure to carry out its WTO obligations.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "476139d0-e18c-4faf-b535-0dd73cdd2d60": {"__data__": {"id_": "476139d0-e18c-4faf-b535-0dd73cdd2d60", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "63de28783fdc11fb41581e8d51ff6590ac33fbc9583056967648d830663856a1"}}, "hash": "63de28783fdc11fb41581e8d51ff6590ac33fbc9583056967648d830663856a1", "text": "Once the process starts, it moves ef\ufb01ciently. There are \ufb01xed time limits for various steps. The \ufb01rst step is to give notice to the other country and seek consultation. The objective is to \ufb01nd solutions to the problem without entering into the formal dispute process. If no agreement is concluded within 60 days, the country moves its contention to the Dispute Settlement Body, which will form a panel for settling the dispute. The DSB must decide on a panel immediately; it cannot delay the formation of a panel beyond two meetings. In general, the panel is composed of three independent experts. They consider the case of both sides and give a report within 6 months. If a party decides to appeal, a bench of three experts in the standing Appellate Body (AB) considers the report of the panel and gives its own report within 60 days. Then the report of the panel/AB is considered by the DSB. The report is adopted by the DSB unless there is consensus that it should not be adopted. This \u201cnegative consensus\u201d provision assures its acceptance, as it is not likely that there will be a consensus not to adopt it. At least one country, the one that the report favours, is bound to oppose the rejection of the report; hence, there cannot be a consensus not to adopt the report. If the report of the panel/AB has found the complaint substantiated, it generally recommends that the defendant country take corrective action. Then that country gives its time frame to implement the recommendations of the panel/AB. This time frame is discussed between the two parties. In case there is disagreement on the time frame, there is a provision for arbitration within 90 days. The arbitrator has the guideline in the DSU that generally the reasonable time for full implementation should not exceed 15 months. In case the defendant country does not implement the recommendations of the panel/AB or if the implementation is found to be de\ufb01cient, the complainant country is allowed to take retaliatory measures. Usually these are in the form of increased tariffs on some products imported from the defendant country. Bene\ufb01ts and problems for developing countries The dispute settlement process must be conducted within a \ufb01xed time schedule, and there is no scope for delaying implementation of the recommendations. Thus, the dispute settlement process is a reassuring measure that the recommendations will be implemented according to WTO rules; in general, recommendations are implemented in good faith. As a result, developing countries that are seen as weaker partners in the WTO have reasonable assurance that their grievances will be redressed. However, developing countries face several problems with respect to the dispute settlement process. Some important problems are noted below. First, as mentioned in the chapter on Bouquets and Brickbats, the ultimate weapon for enforcement is retaliation, which is highly impractical for a developing country if a major developed country is on the other side. - 24 - Second, even if the recommendation is implemented, the full relief may take as long as 30 months, in accordance with the time frame for various stages in the DSU. Third, the relief is only prospective; there is no retrospective relief. Finally, the dispute settlement process is costly; thus, a developing country will weigh this option carefully before entering into it. These problems would indicate that there is an imbalance in the capacity to enforce the rights and obligations between a weak developing country and a strong developed country. - 25 - 7. WTO PROCESS Negotiating process It is important to understand the negotiating process in the WTO in order to appreciate why developing countries feel dissatis\ufb01ed and frustrated. The process from the stage of proposal to that of conclusion is brie\ufb02y described below. A proposal is formally made by a country when it tables a paper in the relevant body of the WTO, i.e., the General Council or the council that handles the relevant subject. Then it is put on the agenda of that council. In a formal meeting the country makes a brief statement, followed by quick statements by other countries. The chairperson of the meeting announces that statements have been noted, the proposal will be kept on record, and there will be consultations on it. Thereafter, the speed with which the proposal is handled depends on the importance of the proposal and the \u201cstrength\u201d of the country tabling it. The chairperson, with the assistance of the WTO Secretariat, arranges for informal consultations among the interested countries. The selection of the countries for consultation is made on the basis of perceived interest in the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "699aa1fd-564f-436b-a327-767fae8e5efc": {"__data__": {"id_": "699aa1fd-564f-436b-a327-767fae8e5efc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f4a49032bc011243c3b1ffca462d5ca64eb689812c6e8fc60d58840434bee6d0"}}, "hash": "f4a49032bc011243c3b1ffca462d5ca64eb689812c6e8fc60d58840434bee6d0", "text": "matter. Generally, in these small-group consultations almost all developed countries are represented one way or another. Only a few developing countries are present. If the proposal is important, the chairperson makes interim reports in the open meetings of the relevant WTO body that he/she is continuing with the consultations. A brief summary of the issues being discussed may be given on some occasions. Finally, when an agreement is reached in the consultations, the chairperson announces it in an open meeting of the WTO body and places it for approval/adoption by the body. It is usually approved, since a country that has not participated would hesitate to hold up agreement at this stage. In this manner, agreements are reached in small-group consultations and \ufb01nally adopted by the WTO body. A large number of developing countries are not present during these consultations. Most only see the proposal in the beginning and at the end. The rights and obligations involved in the agreement are binding to all countries, however, whether or not they have participated in the consultation process. A somewhat similar process is applied during comprehensive negotiations, e.g., Ministerial Conferences or General Council meetings that cover many subjects altogether. Very little is accomplished in open formal meetings. Negotiations are conducted mostly in small groups; then results are brought before the larger bodies for consideration and approval. Developing countries have been expressing concern at such restricted and non-inclusive negotiating processes during the various Ministerial Conferences. Strengths and weaknesses of developed and developing countries Developed countries coordinate among themselves during the preparations and actual negotiations. Their governments regularly consult with their industry, trade and services sectors. In this way, the political and strategic strengths of governments are combined with the economic and technological muscle of multinational \ufb01rms. This union results in a formidable force. Major developed countries begin by clearly identifying their objectives in the negotiations; they undertake intense technical work in the preparation of proposals and supporting arguments, and they cooperate closely at all stages. With respect - 26 - to pressuring developing countries, they often divide the task among themselves in order to be most effective. On the other hand, developing countries are weak in the preparation of proposals and in negotiations. The subjects of negotiations are very complex. Developing countries, except perhaps a very few, are not adequately equipped to handle them. In addition, they suffer from a lack of con\ufb01dence in taking strong positions, since their economies are very vulnerable. The role of developing countries in these negotiations has also changed signi\ufb01cantly: Earlier, they negotiated to receive concessions, while now negotiations are more about their giving concessions to developed countries, which is a dif\ufb01cult exercise. In general, when major developed countries decide to bring a subject to the GATT/WTO arena in order to \ufb01nd agreement, they do not give up easily, even if the topic is promptly rejected by developing countries. They keep it alive in some manner and proceed later. Often they use a step-by- step approach, or \u201csalami technique.\u201d There may be a decision just to study the subject in the GATT/WTO. Then developed countries try to raise the subject\u2019s status to negotiation and come to a modest agreement if all their demands are not fully met. In the process of implementation and review of the agreement, they try to expand the scope of coverage and the level of obligation. An important example is the area of services, which has a history of expansion of coverage right from the GATT Ministerial Meeting of 1982 up to the most recent negotiation. Developed countries have tried similar techniques with the \u201cSingapore issues\u201d -- to be discussed in the chapter on new issues -- but these techniques have not succeeded so far in these new areas. It is important to keep in mind, however, that these issues have not been excluded from the agenda of the WTO; they have merely been excluded from the Doha negotiations. The experience of developing countries in the GATT/WTO has been that their numerical strength has not helped them. Despite the rule of \u2018one-country one-vote\u2019 developing countries do not have a decisive voice, while developed countries mostly get what they want, sooner or later. This is the big irony of the GATT/WTO process. The real reason lies in the strengths and strategies of developed countries, as explained above, and the weakness of developing countries. A large number of developing countries remain silent in WTO meetings and discussions. They are generally dif\ufb01dent because of their lack of knowledge on a particular issue under consideration. Sometimes they are indifferent because the subject under consideration may not", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "79e81a52-77ad-4fbd-8188-a9881372901a": {"__data__": {"id_": "79e81a52-77ad-4fbd-8188-a9881372901a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9b9f90c44cf58930fa634f25d242010897c7c44f132b0d715763aaa790b7cd4e"}}, "hash": "9b9f90c44cf58930fa634f25d242010897c7c44f132b0d715763aaa790b7cd4e", "text": "be perceived as directly relevant for their countries. Moreover, they are reluctant to annoy the major developed countries by their opposition. Such hesitation and indifference, however, do not absolve developing countries from the obligations that emerge out of the decisions and agreements. But some change has been noticed recently, as more developing countries have become increasingly vocal. Also, their preparation has improved. All this needs consolidation and strengthening. What should the developing countries do? First, there should be an effective mechanism for determining national interests with respect to a speci\ufb01c proposal, which requires weighing the pros and cons. It is a complex process. Almost everything under consideration in the WTO may have differential impacts on different sections of the population. Through a process of detailed analysis and wide consultation with the stakeholders, the government has to de\ufb01ne what would be in the overall national interest. For this purpose, it is necessary to build structured mechanisms to have consultations and interactions with farmers, industry, trade groups, NGOs, academics, - 27 - media, and so forth. Special mechanism should be established to take into account the interests of vulnerable groups of men and women. The country\u2019s parliament also should remain fully informed about the ongoing negotiations and the emerging agreements. Within the limits of the country\u2019s constitution, the parliaments may issue guidelines to the government on negotiations. Because the WTO agreements now greatly intrude into domestic economic policy, an effective role of the parliaments in developing countries is useful and necessary. It is relevant for the parliament to satisfy itself that the \ufb01nal results of the negotiations can bene\ufb01t the country commensurate with the concessions it has made. An active interest and role of the parliament will keep the negotiating arm of the government alert and cautious. Second, there should be thorough preparation on the subject so that the position of the country is clear and effective in the negotiations. Third, the country should build a coalition with other countries on its proposal and its position. Forming coalitions on speci\ufb01c subjects and issues is, of course, a necessity, but it is also useful to have ongoing coalitions among some countries across the spectrum of subjects and issues. Some experiences of past and recent coalitions are worth recalling. Developing countries have good experiences in forming coalitions in the textiles sector. Textile-exporting developing countries established their own institution for support in the negotiations and for policy coordination in the 1980s; the coalition proved very useful. In the recent negotiations, developing countries have formed various coalitions in the areas of agriculture, industrial tariffs and services. The examples are: Group 20 (a group of developing countries, including Argentina, Brazil, China, Egypt, India, Pakistan, the Philippines, South Africa, Venezuela, etc.) that want developed countries to reduce their tariffs and subsidies; Group 33 (a group of developing countries, with Indonesia as convenor, that focuses on food security, rural development and livelihood security; some countries are both in this group and in Group 20); ABI (Argentina, Brazil and India, which gave a proposal for a relevant coef\ufb01cient based on the current average tariff in the NAMA negotiations); Caribbean countries group (which has made speci\ufb01c proposals in the areas of agriculture and NAMA); Group of 14 developing countries, including Brazil, Indonesia, Kenya, and Malaysia, which have combined to oppose the new proposals of the developed countries in the area of services. Developing countries should consider forming coalitions right at the preparation stage so that they pool their resources for research and analysis. Fourth, developing countries must \u201cspeak out\u201d in the WTO; it is particularly important in a multilateral negotiating process. A basic difference exists between bilateral negotiations and multilateral negotiations in this respect. In bilateral negotiations, if a country remains silent and hears the other country out, it may be advantageous in assessing how far the other side can go. For the same reason, the other side will provoke a country to speak in order to ascertain its position and \ufb02exibility. In multilateral negotiations, on the other hand, if a country is silent it suits the other countries -- particularly those that hold different views -- because then a decision can be taken without any additional complexity arising through the intervention of this country. Hence, in multilateral negotiations it is necessary for a country to take the initiative and voice its views clearly. Fifth, at the end of the negotiations, a developing country should, before accepting the result, \ufb01rst evaluate the outcome to assess - 28 - whether it is: (i) balanced, (ii) in consonance with its development goals, and (iii) possible to implement without excessive additional resources.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "de076a36-7f67-44aa-a607-90a1101b7863": {"__data__": {"id_": "de076a36-7f67-44aa-a607-90a1101b7863", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "30d1463a79f732a026cbd507deb941713f63e9fc86ff3eb8ba941a1a8739d0cb"}}, "hash": "30d1463a79f732a026cbd507deb941713f63e9fc86ff3eb8ba941a1a8739d0cb", "text": "These should be the essential criteria for testing a result before accepting it. The balance of concessions should be judged on the basis of the new rights and obligations as compared to the earlier ones. Often a negotiator may try to justify an agreement on the basis that the country has conceded much less than what had been the demand on it, but that is not a correct reference for assessing a new agreement. The way ahead in the WTO negotiations is going to be extremely dif\ufb01cult. A good feature is that developing countries now have much more information than before. At the same time, civil society groups in developing countries and developed countries have become active, and their efforts and initiatives mostly tend to be supportive of developing countries. - 29 - 8. NEW ISSUES Background The major developed countries brought four new subjects for consideration in the Singapore Ministerial Conference in 1996 and wanted to start negotiations in the WTO to have new multilateral agreements in these areas. These subjects were investment, competition, government procurement, and trade facilitation. A large number of developing countries opposed this move. Developed countries lowered their ambition, and took a decision to simply study these subjects in the WTO. Thus, a foothold in the WTO was ensured. With respect to government procurement, the decision was to work towards a framework for an agreement on transparency in government procurement. After about two years, developed countries again started putting pressure for starting negotiations and concluding agreements in these areas. A large number of developing countries resisted determinedly. Developed countries\u2019 pressure was so intense, however, that the whole WTO system became destabilized, which subsequently led to the collapse of the Cancun Ministerial Conference in 2003. Finally, a decision was taken in the WTO in July 2004 to have negotiations on just one new subject, i.e., trade facilitation, and to drop the other subjects from the Doha negotiations. Thus, the pressure diminished with respect to investment, competition and government procurement. Nevertheless in view of the past tactics of developed countries, it is likely that they may resuscitate the proposals in the future. Hence, it is necessary for developing countries to remain prepared at all times in order to respond to new pressures that may emerge soon after the Doha negotiations are over. The implications of these three new subjects for development are explained in brief below. Investment Having ensured the expansion of the economic space in developing countries for their industries, trade, service providers and innovators through the WTO agreements, developed countries have their sights now on expanding opportunities for their investors in developing countries. They want to ensure their free entry and operation in developing countries, thereby eliminating or limiting the role of governments in regulating the entry and operation of foreign investment. The implications are serious from the perspective of developing countries. Foreign investment may be useful to them in augmenting their \ufb01nancial resources for investment and also for technological development, but the bene\ufb01ts are not automatic. Unguided foreign investment may be harmful in some circumstances. Intervention through government policies and measures is necessary to ensure that foreign investment is really bene\ufb01cial to both parties. Therefore, the government should retain its role in guiding the entry and operation of foreign investment, which is further explained below. In general, the objective of foreign investors is to get high pro\ufb01ts in quick, easy and assured ways. They will decide on sectors for investment, the geographical location, the sourcing of supply of raw materials and other inputs, on the basis of this priority. The priorities of the host government, on the other hand, will be to use foreign investment for the production of exportable goods directly or indirectly; development of essential and critical infrastructure facilities such as power, transport and communications; establishment of production units in speci\ufb01c undeveloped regions; technological upgrading of domestic production; employment and upgrading of - 30 - the skills of the workforce; enhancement of the innate strength of the production process, and so forth. If these two sets of objectives coincide or are harmonized, there is no problem. But generally it is unlikely that this happy coincidence will occur. Herein lies the need for the government to have an effective role in channelling and guiding foreign investment. It is often put forth that a multilateral agreement on investment will improve the \ufb02ow of foreign investment to developing countries. But this may not be correct, because foreign investment depends to a large extent on the economic, political and social environment of the host country, rather than on its policies on the entry and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "099be289-5df0-4ac2-9c21-5513bf7a3bc5": {"__data__": {"id_": "099be289-5df0-4ac2-9c21-5513bf7a3bc5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fbc0129cb4d31a79a192f856b541a1f055ae00a07ebb3dc2ea90caa5e9c5777b"}}, "hash": "fbc0129cb4d31a79a192f856b541a1f055ae00a07ebb3dc2ea90caa5e9c5777b", "text": "operation of investment. Several developing countries, for example, in Africa, have a totally free regime for foreign investment, but are not getting the investment they need. On the other hand, some countries that have tight control on the entry and operation of foreign investment attract foreign investment in a signi\ufb01cant way. Developing countries rightly have not been convinced by such arguments. The objective of the major developed countries, as mentioned above, is to restrict the role of the government. If they succeed, the development options will be curtailed. Hence, developing countries have been opposing a multilateral agreement on investment in the WTO. Competition Another objective of developed countries is to have a multilateral agreement on competition in the WTO that will further restrict the options of governments in developing countries to modulate and guide the operations of foreign \ufb01rms. Basically, they would like developing countries to adopt the competition policies prevalent in developed countries. These competition policies have serious implications. Healthy competition may facilitate the availability of goods and services of better quality at cheaper prices and may encourage improvement in productivity and supply. A good competition policy should achieve these objectives. Yet some con\ufb02icts of interest exist, for example, those between the interests of the consumer and the producer; those between a large and established producer and a new entrant or small producer; and those between the interests of foreign \ufb01rms and domestic \ufb01rms. A country strikes a balance between these con\ufb02icts and decides its competition policy based on its development objectives, which must be a dynamic process. A country normally modulates its competition policy in order to achieve new balances between various con\ufb02icting interests and to ensure healthy competition appropriate to its level of development. Japan is an eminent example because it modulated its competition policy in the process of economic development from the late 1940s to 1980s, in order to suit its needs of fast industrialization. This type of \ufb02exibility is what major developed countries want to curtail in developing countries. Their proposals will constrain developing countries from modulating their development policies according to their own objectives and priorities. Developed countries also want to ensure certain standards of competition policy in developing countries that may be aimed at permitting large foreign \ufb01rms to operate without inhibitions in these countries. In this process, domestic \ufb01rms may be constrained in their growth and may not be able to reach levels of international competitiveness. Gradually domestic \ufb01rms may collapse, leaving the \ufb01eld free for the operations of foreign \ufb01rms. Developing countries have been opposing a multilateral agreement on competition in the WTO because of all these fears. - 31 - Government procurement Government procurement, i.e., purchases for government use, in developing countries has attracted major developed countries because they perceive big market opportunities, which may not be automatically available to their \ufb01rms. Government procurement involves a very large volume of transactions, often much larger than commercial transactions in the country. At present, government procurement is not covered by the disciplines of MFN treatment and national treatment. Therefore, a developing country has the right to freely choose the source of supply for government procurement and it has the right to give preference to the supply from a particular country as well as the supply from domestic sources. The aim of major developed countries is to constrain this freedom in order to ensure full market access in developing countries with respect to government procurement. Facing stiff opposition from developing countries, developed countries limited their ambitions to having an agreement on transparency in government procurement. Of course, such transparency is desirable, particularly in developing countries, because it will lead to improvement in internal decision-making processes and perhaps widen the supply base. Developing countries, however, perceived two main risks in this exercise in the WTO. They feared that the exercise would expand and spill over into the area of market access. They also feared that a multilateral framework on transparency could impose an unduly heavy burden on them. Their apprehensions were fully justi\ufb01ed because the major developed countries continued making announcements at very high levels, stating that the exercise on transparency was only the \ufb01rst step, and the next step would be market access. Also the proposals of developed countries in the area of transparency appeared very much burdensome. Vigilance in the future Some respite exists because these three new issues have been omitted from the ongoing Doha negotiations. But considering the past history of persistence of developed countries, as explained in the chapter on the WTO processes, developing countries should not be complacent. It is very likely that the major developed", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c3b3c46a-204d-40db-a0e4-6f84662ea1e3": {"__data__": {"id_": "c3b3c46a-204d-40db-a0e4-6f84662ea1e3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0d6a9a6d136fbe514ba5dafa567c79998bc07cc2dfd6ea5444f2612081672bdb"}}, "hash": "0d6a9a6d136fbe514ba5dafa567c79998bc07cc2dfd6ea5444f2612081672bdb", "text": "countries will return to these subjects immediately after the end of the Doha negotiations. The danger also exists through the route of bilateral free trade agreements and regional trade agreements. Major developed countries insist on including these subjects in such agreements with developing countries. - 32 - 9. MAIN ISSUES FOR HONG KONG CONFERENCE Background The Hong Kong Ministerial Conference of the WTO was the sixth in the series of these conferences and followed up on the negotiations launched by the Doha Ministerial Declaration in November 2001. Preparations preceded the Conference for about a year, but differences in countries\u2019 positions, particularly between developed and developing countries, appeared too wide to be bridged. The negotiations were held within the twin framework of Doha Ministerial Declaration and the decision of the WTO General Council at the end of July 2004, commonly called the \u201cthe July Framework.\u201d From the 16 initial subjects in the Doha negotiations (with investment, competition and government procurement dropped) three have been at the centre-stage of the negotiations: agriculture, industrial tariffs (more technically called non-agricultural market access, or NAMA), and services. Two subjects sponsored by the developing countries: implementation issues and special and differential treatment, did not move forward because of technicalities and procedural problems. Negotiators repeatedly failed to meet deadlines in these two areas. Other subjects proceeded with lukewarm interest. The state of play in agriculture, NAMA and services is provided below. Agriculture Main areas of negotiation The negotiations at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference were in three main areas: tariffs, domestic subsidies and export subsidies. Other subjects like non-tariff barriers, e.g., stopping imports by the major developed countries on the grounds of protection of health have receded into the background. Export subsidies The July Framework decided that export subsidies, mostly given by the EU in the form of direct payments and by the US as export credit and food aid, would be terminated within a time frame to be decided. It is indefensible that developed countries wanted to give export subsidies for their agricultural products, because that helped push exports into developing countries, which jeopardized farmers\u2019 livelihoods. The Group of 20 (coalition of some developing countries including Argentina, Brazil, China, and India) asked for its abolition in \ufb01ve years. The US had given a similar proposal, but the main provider of export subsidies, the EU, had not been clear on a time frame. The apprehension had been that the EU might consider a much longer period, perhaps more than 10 years. Finally, it was decided in the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference to eliminate the export subsidy by 2013. Domestic subsidies As explained in the chapter on Trade in Goods, domestic subsidies are given by developed countries through three boxes, amber, blue and green, as well as through a de minimis provision. The amber box subsidy was subject to reduction in the AOA. The blue box and green box subsidies were not subject to reduction. The green box had immunity on the grounds that it was not trade-distorting, while the blue box was omitted from a reduction commitment in the Uruguay Round based on the EU\u2019s insistence, even though it was considered to be trade- distorting. The presumption that the green box was not trade-distorting appears incorrect, as - 33 - explained in the chapter on Trade in Goods. Much of the payment through this box goes into enhancing the staying capacity of the farmer, thus encourages unviable production. In this manner, it distorted production and trade. However, the major developed countries were not prepared to have constraints on their \ufb02exibilities in payment through the green box. Recent proposals were for reducing the amber box, blue box and de minimis subsidy separately and also the sum of these three subsidies which was called the total trade-distorting subsidy (TDS). The reduction of TDS was an extremely important matter. The major developed countries have done a lot of \u201cbox shifting\u201d of domestic subsidies in the past -- for example, by removing a subsidy from the amber box to ful\ufb01l the reduction commitment and then putting that amount, or an even higher amount, in the blue or green box. Fortunately, developing countries have acquired detailed information on all these strategies, which helps them in negotiations. Safety against subsidized imports as well as market access opportunities outside depend on the total subsidy, irrespective of the box in which it has been placed. Hence, to eliminate/reduce the TDS -- i.e., the total of all subsidies that have been acknowledged to be trade-distorting -- has been the most relevant. The EU and US had offered to cut their amber box subsidies by", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c11ce046-ba82-4d9a-979a-b860bcd09ff9": {"__data__": {"id_": "c11ce046-ba82-4d9a-979a-b860bcd09ff9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "17c4f67f18e09f2f61130a62dec5e3857739a402ed603e9cea80951086b2ada9"}}, "hash": "17c4f67f18e09f2f61130a62dec5e3857739a402ed603e9cea80951086b2ada9", "text": "70 and 60 percent respectively, their de minimis subsidies by 80 and 50 percent, their blue box subsidies to a ceiling of 5 and 2.5 percent of the agricultural production and their TDS by 70 and 53 percent. These cuts appear impressive, but they will not improve the situation. The proposed cuts were from the permissible levels of subsidies, but the applied levels of subsidies, both in the US and EU, were already lower than the permissible levels. Further, the EU made a domestic plan by which it would reduce its subsidies to even lower levels by 2008. Calculations have shown that the proposed cuts would not reduce the TDS in the US below its applied subsidy, nor would it lower the TDS of the EU below the level it had planned for 2008. In fact, if their proposed cuts were accepted, the US and EU would have had the \ufb02exibility to increase their respective subsidies by as much as US$ 2 billion and 7 billion Euros. Moreover, the new levels of overall subsidy resulting from these offers still would have been high -- nearly 12-13 percent of their agricultural production. Such high subsidies concentrated on a few selected products could result in massive subsidization of these products, if there is no product-speci\ufb01c cap. Furthermore, a new escape route has been proposed through a new blue box that would mainly allow the US to give counter- cyclical payments to farmers (higher amounts when prices are lower). The amounts projected for 2005 and 2006 were US$ 4 billion and US$ 6 billion, respectively. The signi\ufb01cantly wide escape route has been the green box with amounts of US$ 50 billion and 22 billion Euros respectively in the US and EU in 2000, and the possibility of unlimited increases in the future. Developed countries did not want any discipline in the green box. However, the green box as non-trade- distorting is a myth, so there is no reason to keep it immune from reduction. The objective needs to be to eliminate the domestic subsidy in the major developed countries within a speci\ufb01c time frame. Toward that end, there should be effective reduction that is progressive and speedy. The following steps are desirable: First, the target for reduction should be the applied levels of subsidy of the major developed countries, not merely their permissible levels. In addition, the actual reduction should be in the total trade- distorting subsidy. - 34 - Second, the TDS should be eliminated by the end of the implementation period of the agreement in accordance with what would have emerged from the Doha Work Programme negotiations. The most recently applied TDS (irrespective of the permissible level) needs to be reduced by at least 50 percent in the \ufb01rst year of the implementation period. Third, payment of TDS should be exclusively limited to individual farmers; corporate bodies should be excluded. Fourth, there should be a product- speci\ufb01c ceiling on the TDS. Fifth, in the green box subsidy, at least for the direct payment classi\ufb01ed as de- coupled income support, insurance against income loss and investment aid there should be eligibility criterion based on income. For example, only those individual farmers who have average income from all sources that is less than 10 percent of the average annual income in the country should be eligible. Corporate farms should be excluded. Finally, there should be an annual ceiling on payment of the total subsidy, i.e., the trade-distorting subsidy plus the green box\u2019s decoupled direct payments, insurance against income loss and investment aid, to an individual farmer. Market access In the area of market access, there were proposals to reduce tariffs. The proposals did not diverge much so the real problem in this area was the introduction of \u201csensitive\u201d products. This proposal was a likely escape route for developed countries to continue with heavy tariff protection for several important products. The EU proposed as many as 160 sensitive products. It is, however, important that sensitive products should be limited in terms of number and of percentage of domestic production. At the same time, a sensitive product needs to be made ineligible for any special treatment if it is exported beyond a de minimis limit. Special products Developing countries, particularly Group 33, gave proposals to classify some of developing countries\u2019 products as \u201cspecial\u201d products that would need special protection in the interests of food security, livelihoods security, and rural development. The developing countries need to ensure that the criteria of selection of the products are easy and the selected products are allowed adequate and effective protection. Special Safeguard Mechanism Developing countries, particularly Group", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "add306a3-c12b-46f3-825e-cf3925cc200e": {"__data__": {"id_": "add306a3-c12b-46f3-825e-cf3925cc200e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4df82d0032c6b5dbb9aa18c1fde2f751264c58d51249363a8b4665b847d82c83"}, "3": {"node_id": "3d125fd1-1c6c-480f-b3b3-7b5a47250b0d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "59a56b4cc7aba6b6081068379cc0008e38f71c4dfcff49b92dc45181a4de0753"}}, "hash": "0c38d5643fafe2069cbacb89f93f92df173e19b818a5e01ee9a1a26be0b53e92", "text": "33, also proposed a Special Safeguard Mechanism (SSM). Again, major developed countries gave a lukewarm response. Developing countries would need to ensure that there is an easy and effective SSM for them, which would need to be applicable to all products. The trigger would need to be based on an increase in imports over the previous year, or a decrease in price below the previous year\u2019s level. Both additional tariffs and quantitative import restrictions should be admissible as SSM. Special import restrictions It is necessary to protect farmers of developing countries against subsidized imports from developed countries. Toward this end, there should be a provision that as long as developed countries continue with their export subsidies and domestic subsidies, (i.e., TDS and some elements of the green box subsidy mentioned above) developing countries may apply quantitative import restrictions on such subsidized imports from subsidizing sources. This protection would be different from that through the SSM because it would be applied as recourse against only subsidized imports. - 35 - Industrial tariffs The negotiations on industrial tariffs were focused on two issues: i) reduction of bound tariff rates (binding has been explained in the chapter on Trade in Goods) and ii) including more products under \u201cbinding\u201d (coverage of binding). The structures of tariffs in developed and developing countries are very different. The former have full binding coverage and generally low tariffs (on average about 4 percent), though their tariffs on the products of export interest to developing countries are very high compared to the average. These \u201ctariff peaks\u201d and \u201chigh tariffs\u201d in developed countries have been the main concerns of developing countries. Developing countries have comparatively high tariff rates and, in many cases, low binding coverage. Perhaps because the developing countries were not able to put forth their concerns forcefully, it has been decided in the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference that \u201cSwiss Formula\u201d2 will be the basis for tariff reduction in industrial products. The extent of reduction according to this formula depends on the coef\ufb01cient used in it. The coef\ufb01cient sets the ceiling of the tariff. Further, the higher the coef\ufb01cient, less is the reduction in tariff. Thus, now the critical issue is what should be the coef\ufb01cient in the Swiss Formula. The EU initially proposed a coef\ufb01cient of 10 for all except the LDCs and other weaker developing countries. Such a coef\ufb01cient would suit developed countries quite well because their average tariff is generally low as noted above (around 4 percent). They would have been required to cut their tariff on average only marginally, whereas developing countries 2 t1 = (a x t0)/(a + t0), where t0 is the initial tariff, t1 is the \ufb01nal tariff and \u2018a\u2019 is a coef\ufb01cient. A simple transformation makes it 1/ t1 = 1/t0 + 1/a. For t0 = \ufffd, t1 = a; thus \u2018a\u2019 becomes the ceiling for the \ufb01nal tariff. Further, if the initial tariff is a, 2a, 3a or 4a, the \ufb01nal tariff is respectively 1/2 a, 2/3 a, 3/4 a, and 4/5a. that currently have high levels of tariffs would have been required to cut them by large margins. This was contrary to the Doha Ministerial Declaration that had called for less than full reciprocity in concessions from developing countries. Developing countries have suggested that the coef\ufb01cients for both developed and developing countries be vastly different, considering differentials in their tariff structure. Some have suggested coef\ufb01cients of 6 and 30 for developed and developing countries respectively. Argentina, Brazil and India (ABI) suggested a coef\ufb01cient based on the current average tariff. The Caribbean countries added an index of special situations of countries. Some small economies (less than 0.1 percent share in world trade) offered line- by-line tariff reduction of 15 percent without getting into the Swiss Formula. On the binding coverage, developed countries proposed that the currently unbound tariffs in developing countries be covered by binding and reduction. Developing countries appeared prepared to increase their binding coverage signi\ufb01cantly, but they did not want these newly bound tariffs to be reduced.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3d125fd1-1c6c-480f-b3b3-7b5a47250b0d": {"__data__": {"id_": "3d125fd1-1c6c-480f-b3b3-7b5a47250b0d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4df82d0032c6b5dbb9aa18c1fde2f751264c58d51249363a8b4665b847d82c83"}, "2": {"node_id": "add306a3-c12b-46f3-825e-cf3925cc200e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0c38d5643fafe2069cbacb89f93f92df173e19b818a5e01ee9a1a26be0b53e92"}}, "hash": "59a56b4cc7aba6b6081068379cc0008e38f71c4dfcff49b92dc45181a4de0753", "text": "Many developing countries have undergone deindustrialization in the wake of lowering their industrial tariffs, at the suggestion and insistence of international \ufb01nancial institutions. Naturally, developing countries have become apprehensive about taking binding commitments in the WTO. What is important in the area of industrial tariffs is to ensure that: \ufffd Separate coef\ufb01cients exist for developed and developing countries. \ufffd Coef\ufb01cients applicable to developing countries must take into account their present high average level of tariff, which is part of the current framework of rights and obligations in the WTO. - 36 - \ufffd Tariff peaks and high tariffs in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e9ab11b5-39e6-4194-b4f8-ae9aa44bdbbf": {"__data__": {"id_": "e9ab11b5-39e6-4194-b4f8-ae9aa44bdbbf", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8b325dab643310055358dfe2357a3df835ad900c2ae99b6cd90fd842308f3964"}, "3": {"node_id": "3803e28b-bfa6-4479-905c-d1c4c65e4367", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3bf2d421e5ba19915f3eb84949e192d948090876e78eed3821e0530b7e489bc2"}}, "hash": "03691c1c3e69e1ff63c05e57bb963becd879eb8ec2ca4c34aaccf68a4c0dfccc", "text": "developed countries on products of particular interest to developing countries are effectively reduced. \ufffd Developing countries need not rush into full binding coverage. Depending on the importance of the products, they should agree to have a modulated increase in binding coverage. What is important is to have high binding levels in order to ensure \ufb02exible tariff policy in these products. However, the decision in Hong Kong points towards binding in all products. Hence, now the issue will be how high the bound level is. Services Negotiations were proceeding on the basis of a request-offer approach, as explained in the chapter on Trade in Services. Serious problems arose from the new proposals of several developed countries, which used a complementary approach to the negotiations. There are two types of such proposals: (i) benchmarking of liberalization obligations, or quantitative targets for liberalization by all countries and (ii) plurilateral negotiations in speci\ufb01c sectors. The concept of benchmarking or having quantitative targets appears to be inconsistent with the \ufb02exibility given to the developing countries in the GATS to liberalize fewer sectors and fewer transactions. The concept of plurilateral negotiations in speci\ufb01c sectors is inconsistent with this \ufb02exibility if it is compulsory for a developing country to join such negotiations and to undertake obligations. The most appropriate way is to continue negotiations on request-offer approach. Benchmarking or quantitative targets should not be used. Furthermore, if willing countries use the plurilateral approach in some sectors, it should be under two conditions: First, joining these negotiations should be totally voluntary. Second, the results of the plurilateral negotiation should be applied on a MFN basis. It is also important to guard against the inclusion in the negotiations of some critical sectors of social importance, for example, education, public health, and public water supply and sanitation services, which may limit the role of governments in these important activities. Because of stiff resistance from the developing countries, the concept of benchmarking was given up in Hong Kong; but some emphasis has been put on the route of plurilateral negotiations. Least Developed Countries The LDCs have a special position in these negotiations. In both agriculture and NAMA, two special provisions for them are agreed in principle. First, LDCs will not be required to undertake any reduction commitment. Second, developed countries and developing countries that are in a position to do so will give them duty-free and quota-free access for their goods. The Hong Kong Ministerial Conference has decided that there will be duty-free and quota-free access to 97 percent of the products of the Least Developed Countries (LDC). In addition, two other points relevant to the LDCs are under consideration: (i) measures to provide for the erosion of preferences that arise from tariff reductions in agriculture and NAMA, and (ii) measures to treat the issue of high subsidy to the cotton industry in the major developed countries, particularly the United States. In the area of services, appropriate mechanisms will be developed to accord special priority in liberalization to the sectors and modes of interest to the LDCs. These - 37 - mechanisms will need to assist them in identifying their priority sectors and modes of supply, in order to provide targeted and effective technical assistance and capacity building and to develop an effective reporting mechanism. - 38 - 10. POST-HONG KONG DEVELOPMENTS Decisions in Hong Kong and their implications The Hong Kong Ministerial Conference ended with results that were modest. Main decisions and their implications are brie\ufb02y explained below. Agriculture: There are three concrete decisions: (i) export subsidy will end by 2013; (ii) developing countries can self-designate some products as \u201cspecial products;\u201d and (iii) developing countries can retain their permissible de minimis level of domestic subsidy. Industrial tariff (non-agricultural market access, NAMA): There are two speci\ufb01c decisions: (i) reduction of industrial tariff will be done according to the Swiss Formula and (ii) in case of currently unbound tariff, there will be a mark up from the currently applied rates and then reduction will be effected following the formula. These two decisions respectively mean that there will be reduction of tariff on all products and there will be total binding coverage.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3803e28b-bfa6-4479-905c-d1c4c65e4367": {"__data__": {"id_": "3803e28b-bfa6-4479-905c-d1c4c65e4367", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8b325dab643310055358dfe2357a3df835ad900c2ae99b6cd90fd842308f3964"}, "2": {"node_id": "e9ab11b5-39e6-4194-b4f8-ae9aa44bdbbf", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "03691c1c3e69e1ff63c05e57bb963becd879eb8ec2ca4c34aaccf68a4c0dfccc"}}, "hash": "3bf2d421e5ba19915f3eb84949e192d948090876e78eed3821e0530b7e489bc2", "text": "Services: Negotiations will be intensi\ufb01ed with the objectives and approaches that: (i) commitments will be taken at existing levels of market access in Mode 1 (supply of service by the service provider of a country to a consumer located in another country) and Mode 2 (supply of service in a country to the consumer coming from another country); and (ii) in respect of Mode 3 (supply of service through commercial presence of a foreign \ufb01rm), there will be enhanced", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "346bff9a-f293-4a40-a6b6-09b4c179ddde": {"__data__": {"id_": "346bff9a-f293-4a40-a6b6-09b4c179ddde", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "852c835fb0a4c1990c12086b6b32f26f2b6b3e1f19cc5e1d57abb3cbc9f6a730"}}, "hash": "852c835fb0a4c1990c12086b6b32f26f2b6b3e1f19cc5e1d57abb3cbc9f6a730", "text": "levels of foreign equity participation and elimination or substantial reduction of necessity criteria applied by a country. Least Developing Countries (LDC): There will be duty-free and quota-free access to 97 percent of the products of the Least Developed Countries (LDC). This decision, though very positive, has two points of weakness. There is no decision how this percentage will be determined. Further, the exemption to the extent of 3 percent may allow the major developed countries to stop access of the products in which the LDCs really have export interest. Trade-Related Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPS): There is a decision to amend Article 31 of the Agreement on TRIPS to facilitate export of drugs produced under compulsory license to the developing countries that do not have adequately developed manufacturing capacity. Some experts have raised doubts whether the decision will really give bene\ufb01t to these countries in view of the procedural complexity involved. The implication of the decisions in the areas of agriculture, NAMA and services is that whereas there was no move by the major developed countries on eliminating/ reducing their domestic subsidy in agriculture or liberalizing access in Mode 4 of services which have been some of the major concerns of the developing countries, they have already extracted substantial commitments from the developing countries in the areas of NAMA and services. The decision on agriculture allows the major developed countries to continue export subsidy until 2013. Self-designation of special products by the developing countries is a positive move, but it may be ineffective in absence of specifying the number of products to be selected and the special treatment that will be accorded to them. The de minimis subsidy of the developing countries has really - 39 - never been an issue; perhaps the developed countries have raised it as a strategy. Whereas the gains of the developing countries in agriculture are modest, their commitments in NAMA and services are signi\ufb01cant since they have given up their major options and \ufb02exibility in these areas. Never before in the history of GATT/WTO, had the developing countries agreed to cover each of their industrial products by tariff reduction. Earlier they had merely agreed to reduce the average of their industrial tariff, keeping to themselves the option to spread the average across the range of tariff lines in accordance with their development needs and strategy. Now this \ufb02exibility is lost. Similarly, the developing countries have had the \ufb02exibility to keep a number of their industrial tariff lines unbound, which forms a part of the current rights and obligations in the GATT/WTO. The decision in NAMA takes away this right. In the areas of services, the developing countries have already made commitments in Modes 1, 2 and 3, as mentioned above without any commensurate gains to them in Mode 4. In this way, the results in Hong Kong have followed the usual pattern of GATT/ WTO negotiations wherein the developing countries are made to concede much without commensurate gains to them. Post-Hong Kong negotiating process After the intense negotiations since July 2004, the result of Hong Kong was disappointing. Failure to have any breakthrough highlighted the complexity of issues under negotiation and widely divergent interests of countries actively involved in the negotiations. Efforts continued after the Hong Kong Conference; but the main negotiations were conducted in rather restricted and exclusive format with little transparency. The commissioner of the European Commission, representing the European Union (EU), and the ministers of Australia, Brazil, India, Japan, and the US (jointly called \u201cG6\u201d in WTO parlance) assumed the role of prime-movers and started intense talks among themselves to \ufb01nd common ground. The vast majority of WTO membership was not involved in this process. Naturally they were disturbed and expressed their voices of concern from time to time. But the process went along. Much to the frustration of the six prime-movers, however, the events did not turn out quite as they had expected. There was no agreement among the G6 and the talks collapsed in the last week of July 2006. The usual blame-game followed with bitter comments from various members of G6. They decided to suspend their joint deliberation. The Director General of the WTO decided to suspend the negotiating process altogether and informed the Trade Negotiating Committee and the General Council about the suspension. Neither a formal approval was sought from the General Council nor did it formally give its approval; it simply took note of the statement of the DG. Thus, though the countries accepted the suspension, they did not give their seal of approval. Chances of resumption Now the Doha negotiations have fallen into grave", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "eb62d305-bc6c-472d-9fa0-253b0b66a0cd": {"__data__": {"id_": "eb62d305-bc6c-472d-9fa0-253b0b66a0cd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "38d323c0676602f29c03a915680b2d26e97c139052a35d89ec749a61f9868eb3"}}, "hash": "38d323c0676602f29c03a915680b2d26e97c139052a35d89ec749a61f9868eb3", "text": "uncertainty. Some observers and experts have expressed doubts whether the negotiations will restart soon and get completed to catch the deadline of the \u201cfast track authority\u201d given by the US Congress to the US executive which expires at the end of June 2007. (This authority enables the US President to submit a trade agreement to the US Congress for acceptance or rejection in its entirety without any scope for changes and amendments.) Yet, there is another side of the picture. The major developed countries have within their grips some signi\ufb01cant concessions from the developing countries - 40 - that they may not like to slip away. They already have the decision of total binding coverage and line-by-line reduction of industrial tariff in the developing countries, as explained earlier. According to their perception, an industrial tariff ceiling of 20 percent (resulting from the coef\ufb01cient of 20 in the Swiss formula) and 35-45 percent reduction in the agricultural tariff in the developing countries are within reach. Besides, signi\ufb01cant liberalization in several services sectors through sectoral plurilateral negotiations also appears approachable. The resulting opportunities for enhanced market access in goods and services in the developing countries may be too important for the major developed countries to ignore. Their manufacturers, exporters and service providers are likely to push the governments to consolidate these gains. The time limit of the fast track authority of the US Congress is of course a material factor in the feasibility of concluding the negotiations. The US executive has to notify the Congress of the agreement by the end of June 2007 which works as the \ufb01nal time target. Some time is needed for the US executive to prepare the noti\ufb01cation. And adequate time is required by the WTO Members to prepare their commitment schedules. The latter may be a time consuming process as the work is complex. But it may be possible to do all this under extreme pressure of time, if the negotiations are not delayed too long. Considering all aspects, it is likely that the developing countries may be caught by a sudden turn of events, leading to the whirlpool of negotiations. Hence, it is prudent that they remain prepared for a renewed negotiation. Points of caution Two points of caution are important. First, it should be recognised that the restrictive and non-inclusive negotiating process as exempli\ufb01ed in the past by mini- ministerial meetings and G6 meetings has not succeeded. It is imperative that the negotiating process is made fully inclusive and totally transparent. The entire membership of the WTO, particularly those that are normally left out of the core negotiations, have to take a lead in making the negotiations inclusive and transparent. Second, there are causes for concern with the type of negotiating results and negotiating trends that seemed to emerge towards the end of July 2006 as explained below. Agriculture In agriculture, even if the proposals put forward by G20 are accepted, it may not help the developing countries effectively. While the attention was rightly focused on reducing the total trade-distorting subsidy, there are two loopholes because of which the commitments of the major developed countries will not be of much use to the developing countries. Even if the EU and the US reduce their total TDS respectively to Euro 27 billion and US$ 12 billion (as required in G20\u2019s proposal), they can still go on enhancing their domestic subsidy by giving it through the route of the green box. Further, the reduced levels of the total TDS, if concentrated on a small number of products, can give arti\ufb01cial competitive strength to these selected products. Both these loopholes have to be effectively plugged. The green box subsidy, particularly those in the form of de-coupled income support, insurance against income loss and investment aid, given respectively under paragraphs 6, 7 and 11 of Annex 2 to the Agreement on Agriculture, must be subjected to some criteria of eligibility and ceiling. For example: (i) these payment should be made only to individual farmers, thus totally excluding the corporate entities, (ii) even among the individual farmers, only the less - 41 - af\ufb02uent ones should be eligible, for example, only those having annual income (from all sources) up to 10 percent of the average annual income in the country and (iii) there should be a ceiling on the amount of annual payment to an individual farmer, say, US$ 5,000-10,000. To safeguard against concentration of the total TDS on a limited number of products, there should be a product-speci\ufb01c ceiling. As the subsidies have been high in the past, the ceiling should not be based on historical", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dd514d95-b2c6-4b4a-9522-98c557337cc0": {"__data__": {"id_": "dd514d95-b2c6-4b4a-9522-98c557337cc0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "09210191f618f7b7821150aed8dd0c0e331da146ff045f44f71e09e0d031051a"}}, "hash": "09210191f618f7b7821150aed8dd0c0e331da146ff045f44f71e09e0d031051a", "text": "levels. It should be based on some other criterion, for example, as a certain percentage of the annual production. Over and above, it is important for the developing countries to make bolder proposals on the TDS and in some other areas. Developing countries should be enabled to impose quantitative import restrictions on the products that have received TDS or green box subsidy of the types mentioned above. Sensitive products should be limited in terms of number and also in terms of percentage of domestic production. Further, such a product should be ineligible for special treatment if it is exported beyond a de minimis limit. NAMA In the area of NAMA, the proposals under serious consideration are iniquitous. The current \ufb01gures under consideration for the coef\ufb01cient in the Swiss Formula are: 20-30 for the developing countries and around 10 for the developed countries. Taking 30 as coef\ufb01cient for the developing countries, their tariff of 28 percent, which is their average tariff, will be reduced to 14 percent, thus causing a tariff reduction of 50 percent. At the same time, taking 10 as coef\ufb01cient for the developed countries, their tariff of 4 percent, which is their current average tariff, will be reduced to 3 percent, i.e., only by 25 percent. This will be a clear reversal of the agreed principle of \u201cless than full reciprocity\u201d for the developing countries and will be unfair. Hence, a radical departure from the current consideration of the coef\ufb01cients is essential. Let us start with the targets for reduction of tariff in the developed countries and the developing countries respectively by 60 percent and 40 percent. For such reduction in their respective tariffs of 4 and 30, which are close to their respective averages, the coef\ufb01cient for the developed countries should be 2.7 (or 3, after rounding off) and that for the developing countries should be 45. Now that the Swiss Formula has been accepted in Hong Kong as the basis for tariff reduction exercise, the real issue is the coef\ufb01cient to be used in this formula. These are the coef\ufb01cients which the developing countries should be working for. Services In the services, the format of plurilateral sectoral negotiation has become almost a norm and it is likely to work against the interest of the developing countries if adequate precautions are not taken. Plurilateral track of negotiation is, by de\ufb01nition, on commitments in individual sectors/modes. Thus, each of these tracks works in its own groove and is naturally limited in the negotiating scope within that groove. But a real give-and-take in services negotiation is practical only across the sectors and modes. For example, the developing countries have interest in the commitments of the developed countries in Mode 4 (supply of service by movement of persons), while the major developed countries will push for the developing countries\u2019 commitments in Mode 3 (supply of service by the presence of \ufb01rms). If these two sets of negotiations are conducted in the separate grooves of the respective plurilateral groups, there will be no effective give-and-take across these issues. There is a risk that the developing countries may be forced to commit much in Mode 3 with only a limited gain in Mode 4. A proper - 42 - balance in the outcome can be possible if there is a mechanism of taking these two tracks together. An important strategy of the developing countries should be to balance their commitments in Mode 3 with the concessions given by the major developed countries in Mode 4 and also in respect of standards and domestic regulations which often act as barriers to service exports from the developing countries. Other areas Apart from these three areas currently under emphasis, it is also important for the developing countries to bring the development topics of their interest to the centre-stage of negotiations. Some of these items are: special and differential treatment of developing countries, implementation issues and non-tariff barriers in agriculture and industrial products. Finally Though lip service is given to the development objectives from time to time the focus in the crucial phases of the current negotiation invariably shifts to enhancing market access, often ignoring the adverse impact on development. Vast majority of the membership of the WTO are often frustrated by the tendency of the major developed countries to exert intense pressure for expanding the economic space of their manufacturers, traders, investors and inventors in the developing countries, while the development needs get ignored and development objectives are pushed aside. Besides, there has been a spate of regional trading agreements and bilateral trading agreements in recent years wherein the developing countries are pressurized", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b2f24396-edf4-420a-b201-ae91f97ce60a": {"__data__": {"id_": "b2f24396-edf4-420a-b201-ae91f97ce60a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "World Trade Organization: Notes on the Content and Process", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/world-trade-organization-notes-content-and-process", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4c6f03162a334c5e416671d3cd1f001a71d0dea4e20f1bbaa7a6d0afa44c072c"}}, "hash": "4c6f03162a334c5e416671d3cd1f001a71d0dea4e20f1bbaa7a6d0afa44c072c", "text": "to make signi\ufb01cant WTO-plus commitments which constrain their options and \ufb02exibilities further. The membership of the WTO must realize that many countries have joined the organization for the well-being of their people and not for expanding the pro\ufb01t opportunities of a few entities or for catering to the needs of a few countries. It has to be watched whether the renewed negotiations will follow a truly human development path. Eradication of poverty and attaining Millennium Development Goals remain top priorities for the developing countries in national policy and also in bilateral and multilateral agreements; this is what will nurture a healthy international economic relationship, both in the short-term and long-term. - 43 - REFERENCES Das, Bhagirath Lal (1999). The World Trade Organization: A Guide to the Framework for International Trade. London and New York: Zed Books. Das, Bhagirath Lal (2003). The WTO and the Multilateral Trading System: Past, Present and Future. London, New York: Zed Books and Penang, Malaysia: Third World Network. UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo 23 Independence Avenue Colombo 07, Sri Lanka Tel : +94 11 4526400 Fax : +94 11 4526410 Email : rcc.request.lk@undp.org www.undprcc.lk ISBN 955-1416-14-7", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7624477a-d498-45de-842f-1cc98d3c9df1": {"__data__": {"id_": "7624477a-d498-45de-842f-1cc98d3c9df1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-islands-anti-corruption-directory", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Pacific Islands Anti-Corruption Directory", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-islands-anti-corruption-directory", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c12a9a360fc664a173b3470c2d724ff834f6dbaa616ac87121f04331be045fb1"}, "3": {"node_id": "ec893574-375b-480a-8aa0-63024f297d9e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-islands-anti-corruption-directory", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "48741e33fb02e75b787b68d02b3ce93d6da6d2aacdcdba8557b24dd972b7ce44"}}, "hash": "6d207efff70ae29b9061050a98a587c778514992541fc62e422f64009b25bd7b", "text": "This Directory provides contact and functional information about Pacific Island government agencies and civil society organizations that deal with corruption-related matters. Information contained in this document reflects the most current information available from open sources and from contributing countries as of June 2015. Listings have been included where there is either contact information for an agency or information about the agency\u2019s function(s). Corrections or updates to the information contained in this document should be sent to Samita Singh at samita.singh@undp.org. Motif: \u00a9 Kalo Williams. Contents Cook Islands ..................................................................